# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acoustics-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] An acoustic wave is a mechanical wave that transmits energy through the movements of atoms and molecules.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] However, in solids, acoustic waves transmit in both longitudinal and transverse manners due to presence of shear moduli in such a state of matter.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] The acoustic wave equation describes the propagation of sound waves.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] For lossy media, more intricate models need to be applied in order to take into account frequency-dependent attenuation and phase speed.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] Such models include acoustic wave equations that incorporate fractional derivative terms, see also the acoustic attenuation article.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] D'Alembert gave the general solution for the lossless wave equation.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] For $R=1$ the wave becomes a travelling wave moving rightwards, for $R=0$ the wave becomes a travelling wave moving leftwards.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] A standing wave can be obtained by $R=0.5$ .
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] In a travelling wave pressure and particle velocity are in phase, which means the phase angle between the two quantities is zero.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] As an acoustic wave propagates through the volume, adiabatic compression and decompression occurs.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] For adiabatic change the following relation between volume V of a parcel of fluid and pressure p holds ${\partial V \over V_{m}}={-1 \over \ \gamma }{\partial p \over p_{m}}$ where $\gamma$ is the adiabatic index without unit and the subscript m denotes the mean value of the respective variable.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] From this equation it can be seen that when pressure is at its maximum, particle displacement from average position reaches zero.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] During adiabatic change, temperature changes with pressure as well following ${\partial T \over T_{m}}={\gamma -1 \over \ \gamma }{\partial p \over p_{m}}$ This fact is exploited within the field of thermoacoustics.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] The propagation speed, or acoustic velocity, of acoustic waves is a function of the medium of propagation.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] Thus the acoustic velocity increases with the stiffness (the resistance of an elastic body to deformation by an applied force) of the material, and decreases with the density.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] For general equations of state, if classical mechanics is used, the acoustic velocity c is given by $c^{2}={\frac {\partial p}{\partial \rho }}$ with p as the pressure and $\rho$ the density, where differentiation is taken with respect to adiabatic change.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] Acoustic waves are elastic waves that exhibit phenomena like diffraction, reflection and interference.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] Note that sound waves in air are not polarized since they oscillate along the same direction as they move.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] Interference is the addition of two or more waves that results in a new wave pattern.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] Interference of sound waves can be observed when two loudspeakers transmit the same signal.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] At certain locations constructive interference occurs, doubling the local sound pressure.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] And at other locations destructive interference occurs, causing a local sound pressure of zero pascals.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] A standing wave is a special kind of wave that can occur in a resonator.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] In a resonator superposition of the incident and reflective wave occurs, causing a standing wave.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] Pressure and particle velocity are 90 degrees out of phase in a standing wave.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] Consider a tube with two closed ends acting as a resonator.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] At the ends particle velocity becomes zero since there can be no particle displacement.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] Pressure however doubles at the ends because of interference of the incident wave with the reflective wave.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] As pressure is maximum at the ends while velocity is zero, there is a 90 degrees phase difference between them.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] An acoustic travelling wave can be reflected by a solid surface.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] If a travelling wave is reflected, the reflected wave can interfere with the incident wave causing a standing wave in the near field.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] As a consequence, the local pressure in the near field is doubled, and the particle velocity becomes zero.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] Attenuation causes the reflected wave to decrease in power as distance from the reflective material increases.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] As the power of the reflective wave decreases compared to the power of the incident wave, interference also decreases.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] And as interference decreases, so does the phase difference between sound pressure and particle velocity.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] At a large enough distance from the reflective material, there is no interference left anymore.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] At this distance one can speak of the far field.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] Often acoustic absorption of materials is given in decibels instead.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] When an acoustic wave propagates through a non-homogeneous medium, it will undergo diffraction at the impurities it encounters or at the interfaces between layers of different materials.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] This is a phenomenon very similar to that of the refraction, absorption and transmission of light in Bragg mirrors.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] The concept of acoustic wave propagation through periodic media is exploited with great success in acoustic metamaterial engineering.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustic-wave] The acoustic absorption, reflection and transmission in multilayer materials can be calculated with the transfer-matrix method.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Hearing is one of the most crucial means of survival in the animal world and speech is one of the most distinctive characteristics of human development and culture.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Accordingly, the science of acoustics spreads across many facets of human society—music, medicine, architecture, industrial production, warfare and more.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Likewise, animal species such as songbirds and frogs use sound and hearing as a key element of mating rituals or for marking territories.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Art, craft, science and technology have provoked one another to advance the whole, as in many other fields of knowledge.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Robert Bruce Lindsay's "Wheel of Acoustics" is a well-accepted overview of the various fields in acoustics.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The word "acoustic" is derived from the ἀκουστικός (*akoustikós*), meaning "of or for hearing" and "ready to hear", and from ἀκουστός (*akoustós*), "heard, audible", which in turn derives from the verb ἀκούω (*akoúō*), "to hear".
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The Latin synonym is "sonic", after which the term **sonics** used to be a synonym for acoustics and later a branch of acoustics.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Frequencies above and below the audible range are called "ultrasonic" and "infrasonic", respectively.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] In the 6th century BCE, the ancient Greek philosopher Pythagoras wanted to know why some combinations of musical sounds seemed more beautiful than others, and he found answers in terms of numerical ratios representing the harmonic overtone series on a string.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] He is reputed to have observed that when the lengths of vibrating strings are expressible as ratios of integers (e.g.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] 2 to 3, 3 to 4), the tones produced will be harmonious, and the smaller the integers the more harmonious the sounds.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] For example, a string of a certain length would sound particularly harmonious with a string of twice the length (other factors being equal).
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] In modern parlance, if a string sounds the note C when plucked, a string twice as long will sound a C an octave lower.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] In one system of musical tuning, the tones in between are then given by 16:9 for D, 8:5 for E, 3:2 for F, 4:3 for G, 6:5 for A, and 16:15 for B, in ascending order.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Aristotle (384–322 BCE) understood that sound consisted of compressions and rarefactions of air which "falls upon and strikes the air which is next to it...", a very good expression of the nature of wave motion.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] *On Things Heard*, generally ascribed to Strato of Lampsacus, states that the pitch is related to the frequency of vibrations of the air and to the speed of sound.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] In about 20 BCE, the Roman architect and engineer Vitruvius wrote a treatise on the acoustic properties of theaters, including a discussion of interference, echoes, and reverberation—the beginnings of architectural acoustics.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] In Book V of his *De architectura* (*The Ten Books of Architecture*) Vitruvius described sound as a wave comparable to a water wave extended to three dimensions, which, when interrupted by obstructions, would flow back and break up following waves.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] During the Islamic golden age, Abū Rayhān al-Bīrūnī (973–1048) is believed to have postulated that the speed of sound was much slower than the speed of light.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The physical understanding of acoustical processes advanced rapidly during and after the Scientific Revolution.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Mainly Galileo Galilei (1564–1642) but also Marin Mersenne (1588–1648), independently, discovered the complete laws of vibrating strings (completing what Pythagoras and Pythagoreans had started 2000 years earlier).
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Galileo wrote "Waves are produced by the vibrations of a sonorous body, which spread through the air, bringing to the tympanum of the ear a stimulus which the mind interprets as sound", a remarkable statement that points to the beginnings of physiological and psychological acoustics.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Experimental measurements of the speed of sound in air were carried out successfully between 1630 and 1680 by a number of investigators, prominently Mersenne.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Inspired by Mersenne's *Harmonie universelle* (*Universal Harmony*) of 1634, the Rome-based Jesuit scholar Athanasius Kircher undertook research in acoustics.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Kircher published two major books on acoustics: the *Musurgia universalis* (*Universal Music-Making*) in 1650 and the *Phonurgia nova* (*New Sound-Making*) in 1673.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Meanwhile, Newton (1642–1727) derived the relationship for wave velocity in solids, a cornerstone of physical acoustics (Principia, 1687).
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Substantial progress in acoustics, resting on firmer mathematical and physical concepts, was made during the eighteenth century by Euler (1707–1783), Lagrange (1736–1813), and d'Alembert (1717–1783).
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] During this era, continuum physics, or field theory, began to receive a definite mathematical structure.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The wave equation emerged in a number of contexts, including the propagation of sound in air.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Also in the 19th century, Wheatstone, Ohm, and Henry developed the analogy between electricity and acoustics.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The twentieth century saw a burgeoning of technological applications of the large body of scientific knowledge that was by then in place.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The first such application was Sabine's groundbreaking work in architectural acoustics, and many others followed.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Underwater acoustics was used for detecting submarines in the First World War.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Sound recording and the telephone played important roles in a global transformation of society.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Sound measurement and analysis reached new levels of accuracy and sophistication through the use of electronics and computing.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The ultrasonic frequency range enabled wholly new kinds of application in medicine and industry.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] New kinds of transducers (generators and receivers of acoustic energy) were invented and put to use.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] , both suspended on an overhead steel trellis, to synthesize an indoor acoustic environment outdoors.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Acoustics is defined by ANSI/ASA S1.1-2013 as "(a) Science of sound, including its production, transmission, and effects, including biological and psychological effects.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The study of acoustics revolves around the generation, propagation and reception of mechanical waves and vibrations.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The steps shown in the above diagram can be found in any acoustical event or process.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] There are many kinds of causes, both natural and volitional.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] There are many kinds of transduction processes that convert energy from some other form into sonic energy, producing a sound wave.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] There is one fundamental equation that describes sound wave propagation, the acoustic wave equation, but the phenomena that emerge from it are varied and often complex.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The wave carries energy throughout the propagating medium.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Eventually this energy is transduced again into other forms, in ways that again may be natural and/or volitionally contrived.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The final effect may be purely physical or it may reach far into the biological or volitional domains.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The five basic steps are found equally well whether we are talking about an earthquake, a submarine using sonar to locate its foe, or a band playing in a rock concert.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The central stage in the acoustical process is wave propagation.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] This falls within the domain of physical acoustics.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] In fluids, sound propagates primarily as a pressure wave.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] In solids, mechanical waves can take many forms including longitudinal waves, transverse waves and surface waves.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Acoustics looks first at the pressure levels and frequencies in the sound wave and how the wave interacts with the environment.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] This interaction can be described as either a diffraction, interference or a reflection or a mix of the three.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] If several media are present, a refraction can also occur.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Transduction processes are also of special importance to acoustics.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] In fluids such as air and water, sound waves propagate as disturbances in the ambient pressure level.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] While this disturbance is usually small, it is still noticeable to the human ear.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The smallest sound that a person can hear, known as the threshold of hearing, is nine orders of magnitude smaller than the ambient pressure.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The loudness of these disturbances is related to the sound pressure level (SPL), which is measured on a logarithmic scale in decibels.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Physicists and acoustic engineers tend to discuss sound pressure levels in terms of frequencies, partly because this is how our ears interpret sound.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] What we experience as "higher pitched" or "lower pitched" sounds are pressure vibrations having a higher or lower number of cycles per second.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] In a common technique of acoustic measurement, acoustic signals are sampled in time, and then presented in more meaningful forms such as octave bands or time frequency plots.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Both of these popular methods are used to analyze sound and better understand the acoustic phenomenon.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The entire spectrum can be divided into three sections: audio, ultrasonic, and infrasonic.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The audio range falls between 20 Hz and 20,000 Hz.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] This range is important because its frequencies can be detected by the human ear.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] This range has a number of applications, including speech communication and music.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The ultrasonic range refers to the very high frequencies: 20,000 Hz and higher.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] This range has shorter wavelengths which allow better resolution in imaging technologies.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Medical applications such as ultrasonography and elastography rely on the ultrasonic frequency range.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] On the other end of the spectrum, the lowest frequencies are known as the infrasonic range.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] These frequencies can be used to study geological phenomena such as earthquakes.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Analytic instruments such as the spectrum analyzer facilitate visualization and measurement of acoustic signals and their properties.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The spectrogram produced by such an instrument is a graphical display of the time varying pressure level and frequency profiles that give a specific acoustic signal its defining character.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] A transducer is a device for converting one form of energy into another.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] In an electroacoustic context, this means converting sound energy into electrical energy (or vice versa).
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Electroacoustic transducers include loudspeakers, microphones, particle velocity sensors, hydrophones and sonar projectors.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] These devices convert a sound wave to or from an electric signal.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The most widely used transduction principles are electromagnetism, electrostatics and piezoelectricity.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The transducers in most common loudspeakers (e.g. woofers and tweeters), are electromagnetic devices that generate waves using a suspended diaphragm driven by an electromagnetic voice coil, sending off pressure waves.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Electret microphones and condenser microphones employ electrostatics—as the sound wave strikes the microphone's diaphragm, it moves and induces a voltage change.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The ultrasonic systems used in medical ultrasonography employ piezoelectric transducers.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] These are made from special ceramics in which mechanical vibrations and electrical fields are interlinked through a property of the material itself.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] An acoustician is an expert in the science of sound.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] There are many types of acousticians, but they usually have a Bachelor's degree or higher qualification.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Some possess a degree in acoustics, while others enter the discipline via studies in fields such as physics or engineering.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Much work in acoustics requires a good grounding in mathematics and science.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Many acoustic scientists work in research and development.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Some conduct basic research to advance our knowledge of the perception (e.g. hearing, psychoacoustics or neurophysiology) of speech, music and noise.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Other acoustic scientists advance understanding of how sound is affected as it moves through environments, e.g. underwater acoustics, architectural acoustics or structural acoustics.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Other areas of work are listed under subdisciplines below.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Acoustic scientists work in government, university and private industry laboratories.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Many go on to work in acoustical engineering.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Some positions, such as faculty (academic staff) require a Doctor of Philosophy.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Archaeoacoustics, also known as the archaeology of sound, is one of the only ways to experience the past with senses other than our eyes.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Archaeoacoustics is studied by testing the acoustic properties of prehistoric sites, including caves.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Iegor Rezkinoff, a sound archaeologist, studies the acoustic properties of caves through natural sounds like humming and whistling.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Archaeological theories of acoustics are focused around ritualistic purposes as well as a way of echolocation in the caves.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] In archaeology, acoustic sounds and rituals directly correlate as specific sounds were meant to bring ritual participants closer to a spiritual awakening.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Parallels can also be drawn between cave wall paintings and the acoustic properties of the cave; they are both dynamic.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Because archaeoacoustics is a fairly new archaeological subject, acoustic sound is still being tested in these prehistoric sites today.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Aeroacoustics is the study of noise generated by air movement, for instance via turbulence, and the movement of sound through the fluid air.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] This knowledge was applied in the 1920s and '30s to detect aircraft before radar was invented and is applied in acoustical engineering to study how to quieten aircraft.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Aeroacoustics is important for understanding how wind musical instruments work.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Acoustic signal processing is the electronic manipulation of acoustic signals.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Applications include: active noise control; design for hearing aids or cochlear implants; echo cancellation; music information retrieval, and perceptual coding (e.g.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Architectural acoustics (also known as building acoustics) involves the scientific understanding of how to achieve good sound within a building.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] It typically involves the study of speech intelligibility, speech privacy, music quality, and vibration reduction in the built environment.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Commonly studied environments are hospitals, classrooms, dwellings, performance venues, recording and broadcasting studios.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Focus considerations include room acoustics, airborne and impact transmission in building structures, airborne and structure-borne noise control, noise control of building systems and electroacoustic systems.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Bioacoustics is the scientific study of the hearing and calls of animals, as well as how animals are affected by the acoustic and sounds of their habitat.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] This subdiscipline is concerned with the recording, manipulation and reproduction of audio using electronics.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] This might include products such as mobile phones, large scale public address systems or virtual reality systems in research laboratories.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Environmental acoustics is the study of noise and vibrations, and their impact on structures, objects, humans, and animals.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The main aim of these studies is to reduce levels of environmental noise and vibration.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Typical work and research within environmental acoustics concerns the development of models used in simulations, measurement techniques, noise mitigation strategies, and the development of standards and regulations.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Research work now also has a focus on the positive use of sound in urban environments: soundscapes and tranquility.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Examples of noise and vibration sources include railways, road traffic, aircraft, industrial equipment and recreational activities.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Musical acoustics is the study of the physics of acoustic instruments; the audio signal processing used in electronic music; the computer analysis of music and composition, and the perception and cognitive neuroscience of music.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Many studies have been conducted to identify the relationship between acoustics and cognition, or more commonly known as psychoacoustics, in which what one hears is a combination of perception and biological aspects.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The information intercepted by the passage of sound waves through the ear is understood and interpreted through the brain, emphasizing the connection between the mind and acoustics.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Psychological changes have been seen as brain waves slow down or speed up as a result of varying auditory stimulus which can in turn affect the way one thinks, feels, or even behaves.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] This correlation can be viewed in normal, everyday situations in which listening to an upbeat or uptempo song can cause one's foot to start tapping or a slower song can leave one feeling calm and serene.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] In a deeper biological look at the phenomenon of psychoacoustics, it was discovered that the central nervous system is activated by basic acoustical characteristics of music.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] By observing how the central nervous system, which includes the brain and spine, is influenced by acoustics, the pathway in which acoustics affects the mind, and essentially the body, is evident.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Acousticians study the production, processing and perception of speech.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Speech recognition and speech synthesis are two important areas of speech processing using computers.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] The subject also overlaps with the disciplines of physics, physiology, psychology, and linguistics.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Structural acoustics is the study of motions and interactions of mechanical systems with their environments and the methods of their measurement, analysis, and control.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Ultrasonics deals with sounds at frequencies too high to be heard by humans.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Specialisms include medical ultrasonics (including medical ultrasonography), ultrasonic sensors, sonochemistry, ultrasonic testing, material characterisation and underwater acoustics (sonar).
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Underwater acoustics is the scientific study of natural and man-made sounds underwater.
[src:acoustics-physics/acoustics] Applications include sonar to locate submarines, underwater communication by whales, climate change monitoring by measuring sea temperatures acoustically, sonic weapons, and marine bioacoustics.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The **Doppler effect** (also **Doppler shift**) is the change in the frequency or, equivalently, the period of a wave in relation to an observer who is moving relative to the source of the wave.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] It is named after the physicist Christian Doppler, who described the phenomenon in 1842.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] A common example of Doppler shift is the change of pitch heard when a vehicle approaches and recedes from an observer.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Compared to the emitted sound, the received sound has a higher pitch during the approach, identical at the instant of passing by, and lower pitch during the recession.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] When the source of the sound wave is moving towards the observer, each successive cycle of the wave is emitted from a position closer to the observer than the previous cycle.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Hence, from the observer's perspective, the period or time between cycles is reduced, meaning the frequency is increased.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Conversely, if the source of the sound wave is moving away from the observer, each cycle of the wave is emitted from a position farther from the observer than the previous cycle, so the period or time between successive cycles is increased, thus reducing the frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] For waves propagating in vacuum, as is possible for electromagnetic waves or gravitational waves, only the relative velocity between the observer and the source needs to be considered.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] For waves that propagate in a medium, such as sound waves, the velocity of the observer and of the source are relative to the medium in which the waves are transmitted.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The total Doppler effect in such cases may therefore result from motion of the source, motion of the observer, motion of the medium, or any combination thereof.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Doppler first proposed this effect in 1842 in his treatise "*Über das farbige Licht der Doppelsterne und einiger anderer Gestirne des Himmels*" (On the coloured light of the binary stars and some other stars of the heavens).
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The hypothesis was tested for sound waves by Buys Ballot in 1845.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] He confirmed that the sound's pitch was higher than the emitted frequency when the sound source approached him, and lower than the emitted frequency when the sound source receded from him.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Hippolyte Fizeau independently discovered the same phenomenon on electromagnetic waves in 1848.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] In France, the effect is sometimes called "effet Doppler-Fizeau" but that name was not adopted by the rest of the world as Fizeau's discovery was six years after Doppler's proposal.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] In Britain, John Scott Russell made an experimental study of the Doppler effect (1848).
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] For relative speeds much less than the speed of light, the effects of special relativity can be neglected.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] $v_{\text{m}}$ , $v_{\text{r}}$ , and $v_{\text{s}}$ here are not vectors as velocities, but their magnitudes as speeds.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] This relationship predicts that the observed frequency by the receiver will decrease if the distance between the source and receiver is increasing.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Note that the speed of the wave is determined by the medium, not by the speed of the source.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] If the source approaches the observer at an angle (but still with a constant speed), the observed frequency that is first heard is higher than the object's emitted frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] When the observer is very close to the path of the object, the transition from high to low frequency is very abrupt.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] When the observer is far from the path of the object, the transition from high to low frequency is gradual.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Assuming a stationary observer and a wave source moving towards the observer at (or exceeding) the speed of the wave, the Doppler equation predicts an infinite (or negative) frequency as from the observer's perspective.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Thus, the Doppler equation is inapplicable for such cases.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] If the wave is a sound wave and the sound source is moving faster than the speed of sound, the resulting shock wave creates a sonic boom.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Lord Rayleigh predicted the following effect in his classic book on sound: if the observer were moving from the (stationary) source at twice the speed of sound, a musical piece *previously* emitted by that source would be heard in correct tempo and pitch, but as if played *backwards*.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] A siren on a passing emergency vehicle will start out higher than its stationary pitch, slide down as it passes, and continue lower than its stationary pitch as it recedes from the observer.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] In other words, if the siren approached the observer directly, the pitch would remain constant, at a higher than stationary pitch, until the vehicle hit him, and then immediately jump to a new lower pitch.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The Doppler effect for electromagnetic waves such as light is of widespread use in astronomy to measure the speed at which stars and galaxies are approaching or receding from us, resulting in so called blueshift or redshift, respectively.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] This may be used to detect if an apparently single star is, in reality, a close binary, to measure the rotational speed of stars and galaxies, or to detect exoplanets.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] This effect typically happens on a very small scale; there would not be a noticeable difference in visible light to the unaided eye.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The use of the Doppler effect in astronomy depends on knowledge of precise frequencies of discrete lines in the spectra of stars.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Among the nearby stars, the largest radial velocities with respect to the Sun are +308 km/s (BD-15°4041, also known as LHS 52, 81.7 light-years away) and −260 km/s (Woolley 9722, also known as Wolf 1106 and LHS 64, 78.2 light-years away).
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Positive radial speed means the star is receding from the Sun, negative that it is approaching.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The relationship between the expansion of the universe and the Doppler effect is not simply caused by the source moving away from the observer.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] In cosmology, the redshift of expansion is considered separate from redshifts due to gravity or Doppler motion.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Distant galaxies also exhibit peculiar motion distinct from their cosmological recession speeds.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] If redshifts are used to determine distances in accordance with Hubble's law, then these peculiar motions give rise to redshift-space distortions.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The Doppler effect is used in some types of radar to measure the velocity of detected objects.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] A radar beam is fired at a moving target – e.g. a motor car, as police use radar to detect speeding motorists – as it approaches to or recedes from the radar source.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] In the case of a car moving away from the source, each successive radar wave has to travel farther to reach the car, before being reflected and re-detected near the source.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] As each wave has to move farther, the gaps between the wave crests increase, increasing the wavelength of the radiation returning to the radar.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] In the opposite case, when the radar beam is fired at the moving car as it approaches, each successive wave travels a lesser distance, decreasing the wavelength.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] In either situation, calculations from the Doppler effect accurately determine the car's speed.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] For instance, a police radar operating at 24.15 GHz (K-band) detecting a vehicle traveling at 30 m/s (108 km/h) will measure a Doppler shift of approximately 4.83 kHz, a change easily detected by modern digital signal processing.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Moreover, the proximity fuze, developed during World War II, relies upon Doppler radar to detonate explosives at the correct time, height, distance, etc.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Bats use echolocation in a similar way to locate moths.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The Doppler shift affects the frequency of the wave incident upon the target (moth).
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] When the wave is reflected back from the moth to the bat, the moth acts as the wave emitter and the bat as the wave receiver.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The frequency of the reflected wave is again Doppler-shifted.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] An echocardiogram can, within certain limits, produce an accurate assessment of the direction of blood flow and the velocity of blood and cardiac tissue at any arbitrary point using the Doppler effect.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] One of the limitations is that the ultrasound beam should be as parallel to the blood flow as possible.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Velocity measurements allow assessment of cardiac valve areas and function, abnormal communications between the left and right side of the heart, leaking of blood through the valves (valvular regurgitation), and calculation of the cardiac output.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Contrast-enhanced ultrasound using gas-filled microbubble contrast media can be used to improve velocity or other flow-related medical measurements.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Although "Doppler" has become synonymous with "velocity measurement" in medical imaging, in many cases it is not the frequency shift (Doppler shift) of the received signal that is measured, but the phase shift (*when* the received signal arrives).
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Velocity measurements of blood flow are also used in other fields of medical ultrasonography, such as obstetric ultrasonography and neurology.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Velocity measurement of blood flow in arteries and veins based on Doppler effect is an effective tool for diagnosis of vascular problems like stenosis.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Instruments such as the laser Doppler velocimeter (LDV), Acoustic Doppler current profiler (ADCP), and acoustic Doppler velocimeter (ADV) have been developed to measure velocities in a fluid flow.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The LDV emits a light beam, and the ADCP and ADV emits an ultrasonic acoustic burst, and measure the Doppler shift in wavelengths of reflections from particles moving with the flow.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The actual flow is computed as a function of the water velocity and phase.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] This technique allows non-intrusive flow measurements, at high precision and high frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Developed originally for velocity measurements in medical applications (blood flow), Ultrasonic Doppler Velocimetry (UDV) can measure in real time complete velocity profile in almost any liquids containing particles in suspension such as dust, gas bubbles, emulsions.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Flows can be pulsating, oscillating, laminar or turbulent, stationary or transient.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The Doppler shift can be exploited for satellite navigation such as in Transit and DORIS.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Doppler also needs to be compensated in satellite communication.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Fast moving satellites can have a Doppler shift of dozens of kilohertz relative to a ground station.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The speed, thus magnitude of Doppler effect, changes due to earth curvature.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Dynamic Doppler compensation, where the frequency of a signal is changed progressively during transmission, is used so the satellite receives a constant frequency signal.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The additional Doppler shift due to the satellite moving can be described as: $f_{\rm {D,sat}}={\frac {v_{\rm {rel,sat}}}{\lambda _{\rm {c}}}}$ where $v_{\rm {rel,sat}}$ is the relative speed of the satellite.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The Leslie speaker, most commonly associated with and predominantly used with the famous Hammond organ, takes advantage of the Doppler effect by using an electric motor to rotate an acoustic horn around a loudspeaker, sending its sound in a circle.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] This results at the listener's ear in rapidly fluctuating frequencies of a keyboard note.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] A laser Doppler vibrometer (LDV) is a non-contact instrument for measuring vibration.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The laser beam from the LDV is directed at the surface of interest, and the vibration amplitude and frequency are extracted from the Doppler shift of the laser beam frequency due to the motion of the surface.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Dynamic real-time path planning in robotics to aid the movement of robots in a sophisticated environment with moving obstacles often take help of Doppler effect.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Such applications are specially used for competitive robotics where the environment is constantly changing, such as robosoccer.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Since 1968 scientists such as Victor Veselago have speculated about the possibility of an inverse Doppler effect.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The size of the Doppler shift depends on the refractive index of the medium a wave is traveling through.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Some materials are capable of negative refraction, which should lead to a Doppler shift that works in a direction opposite that of a conventional Doppler shift.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] The first experiment that detected this effect was conducted by Nigel Seddon and Trevor Bearpark in Bristol, United Kingdom in 2003.
[src:acoustics-physics/doppler-effect] Later, the inverse Doppler effect was observed in some inhomogeneous materials, and predicted inside a Vavilov–Cherenkov cone.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] All systems, including molecular systems and particles, tend to vibrate at a natural frequency depending upon their structure; when there is very little damping this frequency is approximately equal to, but slightly above, the resonant frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] When an oscillating force, an external vibration, is applied at a resonant frequency of a dynamic system, object, or particle, the outside vibration will cause the system to oscillate at a higher amplitude (with more force) than when the same force is applied at other, non-resonant frequencies.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The resonant frequencies of a system can be identified when the response to an external vibration creates an amplitude that is a relative maximum within the system.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Small periodic forces that are near a resonant frequency of the system have the ability to produce large amplitude oscillations in the system due to the storage of vibrational energy.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Resonance phenomena occur with all types of vibrations or waves: there is mechanical resonance, orbital resonance, acoustic resonance, electromagnetic resonance, nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), electron spin resonance (ESR) and resonance of quantum wave functions.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Resonant systems can be used to generate vibrations of a specific frequency (e.g., musical instruments), or pick out specific frequencies from a complex vibration containing many frequencies (e.g., filters).
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Resonance occurs when a system is able to store and easily transfer energy between two or more different storage modes (such as kinetic energy and potential energy in the case of a simple pendulum).
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] However, there are some losses from cycle to cycle, called damping.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] When damping is small, the resonant frequency is approximately equal to the natural frequency of the system, which is a frequency of unforced vibrations.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Some systems have multiple and distinct resonant frequencies.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] A familiar example is a playground swing, which acts as a pendulum.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Pushing a person in a swing in time with the natural interval of the swing (its resonant frequency) makes the swing go higher and higher (maximum amplitude), while attempts to push the swing at a faster or slower tempo produce smaller arcs.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] This is because the energy the swing absorbs is maximized when the pushes match the swing's natural oscillations.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Resonance occurs widely in nature, and is exploited in many devices.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] It is the mechanism by which virtually all sinusoidal waves and vibrations are generated.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] For example, when hard objects like metal, glass, or wood are struck, there are brief resonant vibrations in the object.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Light and other short wavelength electromagnetic radiation is produced by resonance on an atomic scale, such as electrons in atoms.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Resonance manifests itself in many linear and nonlinear systems as oscillations around an equilibrium point.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] When the system is driven by a sinusoidal external input, a measured output of the system may oscillate in response.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The ratio of the amplitude of the output's steady-state oscillations to the input's oscillations is called the gain, and the gain can be a function of the frequency of the sinusoidal external input.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Peaks in the gain at certain frequencies correspond to resonances, where the amplitude of the measured output's oscillations are disproportionately large.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Since many linear and nonlinear systems that oscillate are modeled as harmonic oscillators near their equilibria, a derivation of the resonant frequency for a driven, damped harmonic oscillator is shown.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] An RLC circuit is used to illustrate connections between resonance and a system's transfer function, frequency response, poles, and zeroes.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Building off the RLC circuit example, these connections for higher-order linear systems with multiple inputs and outputs are generalized.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Consider a damped mass on a spring driven by a sinusoidal, externally applied force.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] where *m* is the mass, *x* is the displacement of the mass from the equilibrium point, *F*0 is the driving amplitude, *ω* is the driving angular frequency, *k* is the spring constant, and *c* is the viscous damping coefficient.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Many sources also refer to *ω*0 as the *resonant frequency*.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] However, as shown below, when analyzing oscillations of the displacement *x*(*t*), the resonant frequency is close to but not the same as *ω*0.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] In general the resonant frequency is close to but not necessarily the same as the natural frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The RLC circuit example in the next section gives examples of different resonant frequencies for the same system.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The transient solution decays in a relatively short amount of time, so to study resonance it is sufficient to consider the steady state solution.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] It is possible to write the steady-state solution for *x*(*t*) as a function proportional to the driving force with an induced phase change, *φ*.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The phase value is usually taken to be between −180° and 0 so it represents a phase lag for both positive and negative values of the arctan argument.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Resonance occurs when, at certain driving frequencies, the steady-state amplitude of *x*(*t*) is large compared to its amplitude at other driving frequencies.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] For the mass on a spring, resonance corresponds physically to the mass's oscillations having large displacements from the spring's equilibrium position at certain driving frequencies.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Also, *ω**r* is only real and non-zero if ${\textstyle \zeta <1/{\sqrt {2}}}$ , so this system can only resonate when the harmonic oscillator is significantly underdamped.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] For systems with a very small damping ratio and a driving frequency near the resonant frequency, the steady state oscillations can become very large.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] For other driven, damped harmonic oscillators whose equations of motion do not look exactly like the mass on a spring example, the resonant frequency remains $\omega _{r}=\omega _{0}{\sqrt {1-2\zeta ^{2}}},$ but the definitions of *ω*0 and *ζ* change based on the physics of the system.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Consider a circuit consisting of a resistor with resistance *R*, an inductor with inductance *L*, and a capacitor with capacitance *C* connected in series with current *i*(*t*) and driven by a voltage source with voltage *v**in*(*t*).
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Rather than analyzing a candidate solution to this equation like in the mass on a spring example above, this section will analyze the frequency response of this circuit.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Taking the Laplace transform of Equation (**4**), $sLI(s)+RI(s)+{\frac {1}{sC}}I(s)=V_{\text{in}}(s),$ where *I*(*s*) and *V**in*(*s*) are the Laplace transform of the current and input voltage, respectively, and *s* is a complex frequency parameter in the Laplace domain.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] An RLC circuit in series presents several options for where to measure an output voltage.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Suppose the output voltage of interest is the voltage drop across the capacitor.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] and no zeros–roots of the polynomial in the transfer function's numerator.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Moreover, for $\zeta \leq 1$ , the magnitude of these poles is the natural frequency *ω*0 and that for $\zeta <1/{\sqrt {2}}$ , our condition for resonance in the harmonic oscillator example, the poles are closer to the imaginary axis than to the real axis.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Evaluating *H*(*s*) along the imaginary axis *s* = *iω*, the transfer function describes the frequency response of this circuit.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Equivalently, the frequency response can be analyzed by taking the Fourier transform of Equation (**4**) instead of the Laplace transform.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] A sinusoidal input voltage at frequency *ω* results in an output voltage at the same frequency that has been scaled by *G*(*ω*) and has a phase shift *Φ*(*ω*).
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The gain and phase can be plotted versus frequency on a Bode plot.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Note the similarity between the gain here and the amplitude in Equation (**3**).
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Here, the resonance corresponds physically to having a relatively large amplitude for the steady state oscillations of the voltage across the capacitor compared to its amplitude at other driving frequencies.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The resonant frequency need not always take the form given in the examples above.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] For the RLC circuit, suppose instead that the output voltage of interest is the voltage across the inductor.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] using the same definitions for *ω*0 and *ζ* as in the previous example.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] This transfer function has the same poles as the transfer function in the previous example, but it also has two zeroes in the numerator at *s* = 0.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Compared to the gain in Equation (**6**) using the capacitor voltage as the output, this gain has a factor of *ω*2 in the numerator and will therefore have a different resonant frequency that maximizes the gain.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] So for the same RLC circuit but with the voltage across the inductor as the output, the resonant frequency is now *larger* than the natural frequency, though it still tends towards the natural frequency as the damping ratio goes to zero.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] That the same circuit can have different resonant frequencies for different choices of output is not contradictory.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] As shown in Equation (**4**), the voltage drop across the circuit is divided among the three circuit elements, and each element has different dynamics.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The capacitor's voltage grows slowly by integrating the current over time and is therefore more sensitive to lower frequencies, whereas the inductor's voltage grows when the current changes rapidly and is therefore more sensitive to higher frequencies.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] While the circuit as a whole has a natural frequency where it tends to oscillate, the different dynamics of each circuit element make each element resonate at a slightly different frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Suppose that the output voltage of interest is the voltage across the resistor.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] This transfer function also has the same poles as the previous RLC circuit examples, but it only has one zero in the numerator at *s* = 0.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Some systems exhibit antiresonance that can be analyzed in the same way as resonance.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] For antiresonance, the amplitude of the response of the system at certain frequencies is disproportionately *small* rather than being disproportionately large.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] In the RLC circuit example, this phenomenon can be observed by analyzing both the inductor and the capacitor combined.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Suppose that the output voltage of interest in the RLC circuit is the voltage across the inductor *and* the capacitor combined in series.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Equation (**4**) showed that the sum of the voltages across the three circuit elements sums to the input voltage, so measuring the output voltage as the sum of the inductor and capacitor voltages combined is the same as *v**in* minus the voltage drop across the resistor.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The previous example showed that at the natural frequency of the system, the amplitude of the voltage drop across the resistor *equals* the amplitude of *v**in*, and therefore the voltage across the inductor and capacitor combined has zero amplitude.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] We can show this with the transfer function.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Rather than look for resonance, i.e., peaks of the gain, notice that the gain goes to zero at *ω* = *ω*0, which complements our analysis of the resistor's voltage.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] This is called **antiresonance**, which has the opposite effect of resonance.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Rather than result in outputs that are disproportionately large at this frequency, this circuit with this choice of output has no response at all at this frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The frequency that is filtered out corresponds exactly to the zeroes of the transfer function, which were shown in Equation (**7**) and were on the imaginary axis.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] These RLC circuit examples illustrate how resonance is related to the frequency response of the system.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The next section extends these concepts to resonance in a general linear system.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Next consider an arbitrary linear system with multiple inputs and outputs.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] This system has a transfer function matrix whose elements are the transfer functions between the various inputs and outputs.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Each *H**ij*(*s*) is a scalar transfer function linking one of the inputs to one of the outputs.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The RLC circuit examples above had one input voltage and showed four possible output voltages–across the capacitor, across the inductor, across the resistor, and across the capacitor and inductor combined in series–each with its own transfer function.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] If the RLC circuit were set up to measure all four of these output voltages, that system would have a 4×1 transfer function matrix linking the single input to each of the four outputs.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Peaks in the gain at certain frequencies correspond to resonances between that transfer function's input and output, assuming the system is stable.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The complex roots of the numerator are called zeroes, and the complex roots of the denominator are called poles.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] For a stable system, the positions of these poles and zeroes on the complex plane give some indication of whether the system can resonate or antiresonate and at which frequencies.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] In particular, any stable or marginally stable, complex conjugate pair of poles with imaginary components can be written in terms of a natural frequency and a damping ratio as $s=-\zeta \omega _{0}\pm i\omega _{0}{\sqrt {1-\zeta ^{2}}},$ as in Equation (**5**).
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The natural frequency *ω*0 of that pole is the magnitude of the position of the pole on the complex plane and the damping ratio of that pole determines how quickly that oscillation decays.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] In the RLC circuit example, the first generalization relating poles to resonance is observed in Equation (**5**).
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The second generalization relating zeroes to antiresonance is observed in Equation (**7**).
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] In the examples of the harmonic oscillator, the RLC circuit capacitor voltage, and the RLC circuit inductor voltage, "poles near the imaginary axis" corresponds to the significantly underdamped condition ζ < 1/ ${\sqrt {2}}$ .
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] A physical system can have as many natural frequencies as it has degrees of freedom and can resonate near each of those natural frequencies.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] A mass on a spring, which has one degree of freedom, has one natural frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] A double pendulum, which has two degrees of freedom, can have two natural frequencies.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] As the number of coupled harmonic oscillators increases, the time it takes to transfer energy from one to the next becomes significant.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Systems with very large numbers of degrees of freedom can be thought of as continuous rather than as having discrete oscillators.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Energy transfers from one oscillator to the next in the form of waves.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] For example, the string of a guitar or the surface of water in a bowl can be modeled as a continuum of small coupled oscillators and waves can travel along them.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] In many cases these systems have the potential to resonate at certain frequencies, forming standing waves with large-amplitude oscillations at fixed positions.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Resonance in the form of standing waves underlies many familiar phenomena, such as the sound produced by musical instruments, electromagnetic cavities used in lasers and microwave ovens, and energy levels of atoms.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] When a string of fixed length is driven at a particular frequency, a wave propagates along the string at the same frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The waves reflect off the ends of the string, and eventually a steady state is reached with waves traveling in both directions.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The waveform is the superposition of the waves.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] At certain frequencies, the steady state waveform does not appear to travel along the string.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] At fixed positions called nodes, the string is never displaced.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Between the nodes the string oscillates and exactly halfway between the nodes, at positions called anti-nodes, where the oscillations have their largest amplitude.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] where v is the speed of the wave and the integer n denotes different modes or harmonics.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The standing wave with *n* = 1 oscillates at the fundamental frequency and has a wavelength that is twice the length of the string.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The possible modes of oscillation form a harmonic series.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Mechanical resonance is the tendency of a mechanical system to absorb more energy when the frequency of its oscillations matches the system's natural frequency of vibration than it does at other frequencies.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] It may cause violent swaying motions and even catastrophic failure in improperly constructed structures including bridges, buildings, trains, and aircraft.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] When designing objects, engineers must ensure the mechanical resonance frequencies of the component parts do not match driving vibrational frequencies of motors or other oscillating parts, a phenomenon known as resonance disaster.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Avoiding resonance disasters is a major concern in every building, tower, and bridge construction project.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] As a countermeasure, shock mounts can be installed to absorb resonant frequencies and thus dissipate the absorbed energy.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The Taipei 101 building relies on a 660-tonne pendulum (730-short-ton)—a tuned mass damper—to cancel resonance.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Furthermore, the structure is designed to resonate at a frequency that does not typically occur.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Buildings in seismic zones are often constructed to take into account the oscillating frequencies of expected ground motion.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] In addition, engineers designing objects having engines must ensure that the mechanical resonant frequencies of the component parts do not match driving vibrational frequencies of the motors or other strongly oscillating parts.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Clocks keep time by mechanical resonance in a balance wheel, pendulum, or quartz crystal.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The cadence of runners has been hypothesized to be energetically favorable due to resonance between the elastic energy stored in the lower limb and the mass of the runner.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Acoustic resonance is a branch of mechanical resonance that is concerned with the mechanical vibrations across the frequency range of human hearing, in other words sound.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] For humans, hearing is normally limited to frequencies between about 20 Hz and 20,000 Hz (20 kHz), Many objects and materials act as resonators with resonant frequencies within this range, and when struck vibrate mechanically, pushing on the surrounding air to create sound waves.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] This is the source of many percussive sounds we hear.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Acoustic resonance is an important consideration for instrument builders, as most acoustic instruments use resonators, such as the strings and body of a violin, the length of tube in a flute, and the shape of, and tension on, a drum membrane.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Like mechanical resonance, acoustic resonance can result in catastrophic failure of the object at resonance.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The classic example of this is breaking a wine glass with sound at the precise resonant frequency of the glass, although this is difficult in practice.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Electrical resonance occurs in an electric circuit at a particular *resonant frequency* when the impedance of the circuit is at a minimum in a series circuit or at maximum in a parallel circuit (usually when the transfer function peaks in absolute value).
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Resonance in circuits are used for both transmitting and receiving wireless communications such as television, cell phones and radio.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] An optical cavity, also called an *optical resonator*, is an arrangement of mirrors that forms a standing wave cavity resonator for light waves.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Optical cavities are a major component of lasers, surrounding the gain medium and providing feedback of the laser light.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] They are also used in optical parametric oscillators and some interferometers.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Light confined in the cavity reflects multiple times producing standing waves for certain resonant frequencies.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The standing wave patterns produced are called "modes".
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Longitudinal modes differ only in frequency while transverse modes differ for different frequencies and have different intensity patterns across the cross-section of the beam.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Ring resonators and whispering galleries are examples of optical resonators that do not form standing waves.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Different resonator types are distinguished by the focal lengths of the two mirrors and the distance between them; flat mirrors are not often used because of the difficulty of aligning them precisely.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The geometry (resonator type) must be chosen so the beam remains stable, i.e., the beam size does not continue to grow with each reflection.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Resonator types are also designed to meet other criteria such as minimum beam waist or having no focal point (and therefore intense light at that point) inside the cavity.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Optical cavities are designed to have a very large *Q* factor.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] A beam reflects a large number of times with little attenuation—therefore the frequency line width of the beam is small compared to the frequency of the laser.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Additional optical resonances are guided-mode resonances and surface plasmon resonance, which result in anomalous reflection and high evanescent fields at resonance.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] In this case, the resonant modes are guided modes of a waveguide or surface plasmon modes of a dielectric-metallic interface.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] These modes are usually excited by a subwavelength grating.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] In celestial mechanics, an orbital resonance occurs when two orbiting bodies exert a regular, periodic gravitational influence on each other, usually due to their orbital periods being related by a ratio of two small integers.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Orbital resonances greatly enhance the mutual gravitational influence of the bodies.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] In most cases, this results in an *unstable* interaction, in which the bodies exchange momentum and shift orbits until the resonance no longer exists.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Under some circumstances, a resonant system can be stable and self-correcting, so that the bodies remain in resonance.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Examples are the 1:2:4 resonance of Jupiter's moons Ganymede, Europa, and Io, and the 2:3 resonance between Pluto and Neptune.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Unstable resonances with Saturn's inner moons give rise to gaps in the rings of Saturn.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The special case of 1:1 resonance (between bodies with similar orbital radii) causes large Solar System bodies to clear the neighborhood around their orbits by ejecting nearly everything else around them; this effect is used in the current definition of a planet.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) is the name given to a physical resonance phenomenon involving the observation of specific quantum mechanical magnetic properties of an atomic nucleus in the presence of an applied, external magnetic field.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Many scientific techniques exploit NMR phenomena to study molecular physics, crystals, and non-crystalline materials through NMR spectroscopy.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] NMR is also routinely used in advanced medical imaging techniques, such as in magnetic resonance imaging (MRI).
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] All nuclei containing odd numbers of nucleons have an intrinsic angular momentum and magnetic moment.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] A key feature of NMR is that the resonant frequency of a particular substance is directly proportional to the strength of the applied magnetic field.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] It is this feature that is exploited in imaging techniques; if a sample is placed in a non-uniform magnetic field then the resonant frequencies of the sample's nuclei depend on where in the field they are located.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Therefore, the particle can be located quite precisely by its resonant frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Electron paramagnetic resonance, otherwise known as *electron spin resonance* (ESR), is a spectroscopic technique similar to NMR, but uses unpaired electrons instead.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Materials for which this can be applied are much more limited since the material needs to both have an unpaired spin and be paramagnetic.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The Mössbauer effect is the resonant and recoil-free emission and absorption of gamma ray photons by atoms bound in a solid form.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Resonance in particle physics appears in similar circumstances to classical physics at the level of quantum mechanics and quantum field theory.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Resonances can also be thought of as unstable particles, with the formula in the Universal resonance curve section of this article applying if *Γ* is the particle's decay rate and $\omega _{0}$ is the particle's mass *M*.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] In that case, the formula comes from the particle's propagator, with its mass replaced by the complex number *M* + *iΓ*.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The formula is further related to the particle's decay rate by the optical theorem.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] A column of soldiers marching in regular step on a narrow and structurally flexible bridge can set it into dangerously large amplitude oscillations.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] On April 12, 1831, the Broughton Suspension Bridge near Salford, England collapsed while a group of British soldiers were marching across.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Since then, the British Army has had a standing order for soldiers to break stride when marching across bridges, to avoid resonance from their regular marching pattern affecting the bridge.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Vibrations of a motor or engine can induce resonant vibration in its supporting structures if their natural frequency is close to that of the vibrations of the engine.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] A common example is the rattling sound of a bus body when the engine is left idling.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Structural resonance of a suspension bridge induced by winds can lead to its catastrophic collapse.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Several early suspension bridges in Europe and United States were destroyed by structural resonance induced by modest winds.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The collapse of the Tacoma Narrows Bridge on 7 November 1940 is characterized in physics as a classic example of resonance.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Scanlan and others that the destruction was instead caused by aeroelastic flutter, a complicated interaction between the bridge and the winds passing through it—an example of a self oscillation, or a kind of "self-sustaining vibration" as referred to in the nonlinear theory of vibrations.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The *Q* factor or *quality factor* is a dimensionless parameter that describes how under-damped an oscillator or resonator is, and characterizes the bandwidth of a resonator relative to its center frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] A high value for *Q* indicates a lower rate of energy loss relative to the stored energy, i.e., the system is lightly damped.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The parameter is defined by the equation: $Q=2\pi {\text{ }}{\frac {\text{ maximum energy stored}}{\text{total energy lost per cycle at resonance}}}$ .
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The higher the Q factor, the greater the amplitude at the resonant frequency, and the smaller the *bandwidth*, or range of frequencies around resonance occurs.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] In electrical resonance, a high-*Q* circuit in a radio receiver is more difficult to tune, but has greater selectivity, and so would be better at filtering out signals from other stations.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Examples that normally have a low Q factor include door closers (Q=0.5).
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Systems with high Q factors include tuning forks (Q=1000), atomic clocks and lasers (Q≈1011).
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The exact response of a resonance, especially for frequencies far from the resonant frequency, depends on the details of the physical system, and is usually not exactly symmetric about the resonant frequency, as illustrated for the simple harmonic oscillator above.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The intensity is defined as the square of the amplitude of the oscillations.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] This is a Lorentzian function, or Cauchy distribution, and this response is found in many physical situations involving resonant systems. Γ is a parameter dependent on the damping of the oscillator, and is known as the *linewidth* of the resonance.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Heavily damped oscillators tend to have broad linewidths, and respond to a wider range of driving frequencies around the resonant frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] The linewidth is inversely proportional to the *Q* factor, which is a measure of the sharpness of the resonance.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] In radio engineering and electronics engineering, this approximate symmetric response is known as the *universal resonance curve*, a concept introduced by Frederick E.
[src:acoustics-physics/resonance] Terman in 1932 to simplify the approximate analysis of radio circuits with a range of center frequencies and *Q* values.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] in pressure, stress, particle displacement, particle velocity, etc., propagated in a medium with internal forces (e.g., elastic or viscous), or the superposition of such propagated oscillation.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] This two-part definition of sound states that sound can be taken as a wave motion in an elastic medium, making it also a stimulus, or as an excitation of the hearing mechanism that results in the perception of sound, making it a sensation.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Such sources typically describe sound as a perturbation in mechanical properties (e.g., pressure or particle motion) that travels through a medium and consists of medium variations (compressions and rarefactions), a formulation adopted for conceptual clarity and scientific precision.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Acoustics is the interdisciplinary scientific study of mechanical waves, vibrations, sound, ultrasound, and infrasound in gaseous, liquid, or solid media.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] A scientist who works in the field of acoustics is called an *acoustician*, while an individual specialising in acoustical engineering may be referred to as an *acoustical engineer*.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] An audio engineer, by contrast, is concerned with the recording, manipulation, mixing, and reproduction of sound.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Applications of acoustics are found in many areas of modern society.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Subdisciplines include aeroacoustics, audio signal processing, architectural acoustics, bioacoustics, electroacoustics, environmental noise, musical acoustics, noise control, psychoacoustics, speech, ultrasound, underwater acoustics, and vibration.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Sound travels as a mechanical wave through a medium (e.g. water, crystals, air).
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Sound waves are generated by a sound source, such as a vibrating diaphragm of a loudspeaker.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] As the sound source vibrates the surrounding medium, mechanical disturbances propagate away from the source at the local speed of sound, thus resulting in a sound wave.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] At a fixed distance from the source, the pressure, velocity, and displacement of the medium's particles vary in time.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] At an instant in time, the pressure, velocity, and displacement vary spatially.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] The particles of the medium do not travel with the sound wave; instead, the disturbance and its mechanical energy propagate through the medium.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Though intuitively expectable for solids, this also applies for liquids and gases.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] The matter that supports the transmission of a sound is named the transmission medium.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Media may be any form of matter, whether solids, liquids, gases or plasmas.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] However, sound cannot propagate through a vacuum because there is no medium to support mechanical disturbances.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Theoretical work indicates that sound waves carry an extremely small effective gravitational mass.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] This mass arises from nonlinear corrections to the stress–energy of the wave, and implies that sound waves both respond to gravity and generate a very weak gravitational field of their own.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] For ordinary equations of state, the effective mass is negative, meaning that sound waves in such media act as if they carry a tiny negative gravitational mass.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] The effect is extremely small because it appears only at nonlinear order in the equations governing wave motion.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Sound waves exhibit behaviours such as reflection, transmission, refraction, diffraction, absorption, and attenuation.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] When sound is moving through a non‑homogeneous medium , it may be refracted (either dispersed or focused).
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Sound is transmitted through fluids (e.g. gases, plasmas, and liquids) as longitudinal waves, also called compression waves.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Through solids, however, sound can be transmitted as both longitudinal waves and transverse waves.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Longitudinal sound waves are waves of alternating pressure deviations from the equilibrium pressure, causing local regions of compression and rarefaction, while transverse waves (in solids) are waves of alternating shear stress perpendicular to the direction of propagation.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Unlike longitudinal sound waves, transverse sound waves have the property of *polarisation*.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Sound waves may be viewed using parabolic mirrors and objects that produce sound.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Although sound transmission involves many physical processes, the signal received at a point (such as a microphone or the ear) can be fully described as a time‑varying pressure.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] This pressure‑versus‑time waveform provides a complete representation of any sound or audio signal detected at that location.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Sometimes speed and direction are combined as a velocity vector; wave number and direction are combined as a wave vector.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] To analyse audio, a complicated waveform—such as the one shown on the right—can be represented as a linear combination of sinusoidal components of different frequencies, amplitudes, and phases.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] The speed of sound depends on the medium the waves pass through, and is a fundamental property of the material.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] The first significant effort towards measurement of the speed of sound was made by Isaac Newton.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] This was later disproven and the French mathematician Laplace corrected the formula by deducing that the phenomenon of sound travelling is not isothermal, as believed by Newton, but adiabatic.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] He added another factor to the equation—*gamma*—and multiplied ${\sqrt {\gamma }}$ by ${\sqrt {p/\rho }}$ , thus coming up with the equation $c={\sqrt {\gamma \cdot p/\rho }}$ .
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Since $K=\gamma \cdot p$ , the final equation came up to be $c={\sqrt {K/\rho }}$ , which is also known as the Newton–Laplace equation.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] In this equation, *K* is the elastic bulk modulus, *c* is the velocity of sound, and $\rho$ is the density.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Thus, the speed of sound is proportional to the square root of the ratio of the bulk modulus of the medium to its density.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Those physical properties and the speed of sound change with ambient conditions.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] For example, the speed of sound in gases depends on temperature.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] The speed of sound is also slightly sensitive, being subject to a second-order anharmonic effect, to the sound amplitude, which means there are non-linear propagation effects, such as the production of harmonics and mixed tones not present in the original sound (see parametric array).
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] If relativistic effects are important, the speed of sound is calculated from the relativistic Euler equations.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] In fresh water the speed of sound is approximately 1,482 m/s (5,335 km/h; 3,315 mph).
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Sound moves the fastest in solid atomic hydrogen at about 36,000 m/s (129,600 km/h; 80,530 mph).
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Without a specified reference sound pressure, a value expressed in decibels cannot represent a sound pressure level.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Since the human ear does not have a flat spectral response, sound pressures are often frequency weighted so that the measured level matches perceived levels more closely.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) has defined several weighting schemes.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] A-weighting attempts to match the response of the human ear to noise and A-weighted sound pressure levels are labeled dBA.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] C-weighting is used to measure peak levels.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] In physiology and psychology, the term *sound* refers to the perceptual experience produced by acoustic stimulation, distinguishing it from the physical definition used in acoustics.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] The field of psychoacoustics and the broader discipline of psychophysics study how organisms detect and interpret such stimuli.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] The physiological reception of sound in organisms with auditory systems is limited to a finite range of frequencies.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] In humans, sensitivity to pitch typically spans from about 20 Hz to 20 kHz, with the upper limit decreasing with age.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Below about 20 Hz, periodic acoustic stimuli may be perceived not as pitch but as discrete pulses or slow amplitude fluctuations.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] The term *sound* is sometimes restricted to vibrations within the human hearing range, though other species exhibit markedly different auditory limits.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] For example, domestic dogs can detect frequencies above 20 kHz.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] As a signal perceived by one of the major senses, sound is used by many species for detecting danger, navigation, predation, and communication.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Earth's atmosphere, water, and virtually any physical phenomenon, such as fire, rain, wind, surf, or earthquake, produces (and is characterized by) its unique sounds.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Many species, such as frogs, birds, marine and terrestrial mammals, have also developed special organs to produce sound.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] In some species, these produce song and speech.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Furthermore, humans have developed culture and technology (such as music, telephone and radio) that allows them to generate, record, transmit, and broadcast sound.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Noise is a term often used to refer to an unwanted sound.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] In science and engineering, noise is an undesirable component that obscures a wanted signal.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] However, in sound perception it can often be used to identify the source of a sound and is an important component of timbre perception (see below).
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Soundscape is the component of the acoustic environment that can be perceived by humans.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] The acoustic environment is the combination of all sounds (whether audible to humans or not) within a given area as modified by the environment and understood by people, in context of the surrounding environment.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] There are, historically, six experimentally separable ways in which sound waves are analysed.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] They are: pitch, duration, loudness, timbre, sonic texture and spatial location.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Some of these terms have a standardised definition (for instance in the ANSI Acoustical Terminology ANSI/ASA S1.1-2013).
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] More recent approaches have also considered temporal envelope and temporal fine structure as perceptually relevant analyses.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Pitch is perceived as how "low" or "high" a sound is and represents the cyclic, repetitive nature of the vibrations that make up sound.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] For simple sounds, pitch relates to the frequency of the slowest vibration in the sound (called the fundamental harmonic).
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] In the case of complex sounds, pitch perception can vary.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Sometimes individuals identify different pitches for the same sound, based on their personal experience of particular sound patterns.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Selection of a particular pitch is determined by pre-conscious examination of vibrations, including their frequencies and the balance between them.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Specific attention is given to recognising potential harmonics.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Every sound is placed on a pitch continuum from low to high.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] For example: white noise (random noise spread evenly across all frequencies) sounds higher in pitch than pink noise (random noise spread evenly across octaves) as white noise has more high frequency content.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Duration is perceived as how "long" or "short" a sound is and relates to onset and offset signals created by nerve responses to sounds.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] The duration of a sound usually lasts from the time the sound is first noticed until the sound is identified as having changed or ceased.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Sometimes this is not directly related to the physical duration of a sound.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] For example; in a noisy environment, gapped sounds (sounds that stop and start) can sound as if they are continuous because the offset messages are missed owing to disruptions from noises in the same general bandwidth.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] This can be of great benefit in understanding distorted messages such as radio signals that suffer from interference, as (owing to this effect) the message is heard as if it was continuous.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Loudness is perceived as how "loud" or "soft" a sound is, and reflects the overall pattern of auditory‑nerve activity produced by a sound.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] In general, louder sounds create greater displacement of the basilar membrane, which stimulates more auditory‑nerve fibres and results in a stronger neural representation of loudness.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Perceived loudness also depends on how sound energy is distributed over time.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] When a sound is very brief, the auditory system does not fully integrate its energy, so it is heard as softer than a longer sound presented at the same physical intensity.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] This process, known as *temporal summation*, operates over a window of roughly 200 ms.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Beyond this duration, increasing the length of the sound no longer increases its perceived loudness.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] The spectral complexity of a sound can also influence loudness perception.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Complex tones, which activate a broader range of auditory‑nerve fibres, are often judged as louder than simple tones (such as sine waves) even when matched for physical amplitude.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Timbre is perceived as the quality of different sounds (e.g. the thud of a fallen rock, the whir of a drill, the tone of a musical instrument or the quality of a voice) and represents the pre-conscious allocation of a sonic identity to a sound (e.g.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] This identity is based on information gained from frequency transients, noisiness, unsteadiness, perceived pitch and the spread and intensity of overtones in the sound over an extended time frame.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] The way a sound changes over time provides most of the information for timbre identification.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Even though a small section of the wave form from each instrument looks very similar, differences in changes over time between the clarinet and the piano are evident in both loudness and harmonic content.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Less noticeable are the different noises heard, such as air hisses for the clarinet and hammer strikes for the piano.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Sonic texture relates to the number of sound sources and the interaction between them.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] The word *texture*, in this context, relates to the cognitive separation of auditory objects.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] In music, texture is often referred to as the difference between unison, polyphony and homophony, but it can also relate (for example) to a busy cafe; a sound which might be referred to as *cacophony*.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Spatial location represents the cognitive placement of a sound in an environmental context; including the placement of a sound on both the horizontal and vertical plane, the distance from the sound source and the characteristics of the sonic environment.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] In a thick texture, it is possible to identify multiple sound sources using a combination of spatial location and timbre identification.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Ultrasound is sound waves with frequencies higher than 20,000 Hz.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Ultrasound is not different from audible sound in its physical properties, but cannot be heard by humans.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Ultrasound devices operate with frequencies from 20 kHz up to several gigahertz.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Medical ultrasound is commonly used for diagnostics and treatment.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Infrasound is sound waves with frequencies lower than 20 Hz.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Although sounds of such low frequency are too low for humans to hear as a pitch, these sound are heard as discrete pulses (like the 'popping' sound of an idling motorcycle).
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] Whales, elephants and other animals can detect infrasound and use it to communicate.
[src:acoustics-physics/sound] It can be used to detect volcanic eruptions and is used in some types of music.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] In physics, a **standing wave**, also known as a **stationary wave**, is a wave that oscillates in time but whose peak amplitude profile does not move in space.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The peak amplitude of the wave oscillations at any point in space is constant with respect to time, and the oscillations at different points throughout the wave are in phase.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The locations at which the absolute value of the amplitude is minimum are called nodes, and the locations where the absolute value of the amplitude is maximum are called antinodes.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Standing waves were first described scientifically by Michael Faraday in 1831.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Faraday observed standing waves on the surface of a liquid in a vibrating container.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Franz Melde coined the term "standing wave" (German: *stehende Welle* or *Stehwelle*) around 1860 and demonstrated the phenomenon in his classic experiment with vibrating strings.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This phenomenon can occur because the medium is moving in the direction opposite to the movement of the wave, or it can arise in a stationary medium as a result of interference between two waves traveling in opposite directions.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The most common cause of standing waves is the phenomenon of resonance, in which standing waves occur inside a resonator due to interference between waves reflected back and forth at the resonator's resonant frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] For waves of equal amplitude traveling in opposing directions, there is on average no net propagation of energy.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] As an example of the first type, under certain meteorological conditions standing waves form in the atmosphere in the lee of mountain ranges.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Such waves are often exploited by glider pilots.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Standing waves and hydraulic jumps also form on fast flowing river rapids and tidal currents such as the Saltstraumen maelstrom.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Many standing river waves are popular river surfing breaks.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] As an example of the second type, a *standing wave* in a transmission line is a wave in which the distribution of current, voltage, or field strength is formed by the superposition of two waves of the same frequency propagating in opposite directions.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The effect is a series of nodes (zero displacement) and anti-nodes (maximum displacement) at fixed points along the transmission line.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Such a standing wave may be formed when a wave is transmitted into one end of a transmission line and is reflected from the other end by an impedance mismatch, *i.e.*, discontinuity, such as an open circuit or a short.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The failure of the line to transfer power at the standing wave frequency will usually result in attenuation distortion.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] In practice, losses in the transmission line and other components mean that a perfect reflection and a pure standing wave are never achieved.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The result is a *partial standing wave*, which is a superposition of a standing wave and a traveling wave.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The degree to which the wave resembles either a pure standing wave or a pure traveling wave is measured by the standing wave ratio (SWR).
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Another example is standing waves in the open ocean formed by waves with the same wave period moving in opposite directions.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] These may form near storm centres, or from reflection of a swell at the shore, and are the source of microbaroms and microseisms.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This section considers representative one- and two-dimensional cases of standing waves.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] First, an example of an infinite length string shows how identical waves traveling in opposite directions interfere to produce standing waves.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Next, two finite length string examples with different boundary conditions demonstrate how the boundary conditions restrict the frequencies that can form standing waves.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Next, the example of sound waves in a pipe demonstrates how the same principles can be applied to longitudinal waves with analogous boundary conditions.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Standing waves can also occur in two- or three-dimensional resonators.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] With standing waves on two-dimensional membranes such as drumheads, illustrated in the animations above, the nodes become nodal lines, lines on the surface at which there is no movement, that separate regions vibrating with opposite phase.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] These nodal line patterns are called Chladni figures.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] In three-dimensional resonators, such as musical instrument sound boxes and microwave cavity resonators, there are nodal surfaces.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This section includes a two-dimensional standing wave example with a rectangular boundary to illustrate how to extend the concept to higher dimensions.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] To begin, consider a string of infinite length along the *x*-axis that is free to be stretched transversely in the *y* direction.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Equation (**1**) does not describe a traveling wave.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] At any position *x*, *y*(*x*,*t*) simply oscillates in time with an amplitude that varies in the *x*-direction as $2y_{\text{max}}\sin \left({2\pi x \over \lambda }\right)$ .
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The animation at the beginning of this article depicts what is happening.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] As the left-traveling blue wave and right-traveling green wave interfere, they form the standing red wave that does not travel and instead oscillates in place.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Because the string is of infinite length, it has no boundary condition for its displacement at any point along the *x*-axis.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] As a result, a standing wave can form at any frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] the amplitude is maximal, with a value of twice the amplitude of the right- and left-traveling waves that interfere to produce this standing wave pattern.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The distance between two consecutive nodes or anti-nodes is half the wavelength, *λ*/2.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Next, consider a string with fixed ends at *x* = 0 and *x* = *L*.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The string will have some damping as it is stretched by traveling waves, but assume the damping is very small.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Suppose that at the *x* = 0 fixed end a sinusoidal force is applied that drives the string up and down in the y-direction with a small amplitude at some frequency *f*.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] In this situation, the driving force produces a right-traveling wave.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] That wave reflects off the right fixed end and travels back to the left, reflects again off the left fixed end and travels back to the right, and so on.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Eventually, a steady state is reached where the string has identical right- and left-traveling waves as in the infinite-length case and the power dissipated by damping in the string equals the power supplied by the driving force so the waves have constant amplitude.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This boundary condition is in the form of the Sturm–Liouville formulation.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The latter boundary condition is satisfied when $\sin \left({2\pi L \over \lambda }\right)=0$ .
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Waves can only form standing waves on this string if they have a wavelength that satisfies this relationship with *L*.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Higher integer values of *n* correspond to modes of oscillation called harmonics or overtones.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Any standing wave on the string will have *n* + 1 nodes including the fixed ends and *n* anti-nodes.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] In this variation of the expression for the wavelength, *n* must be even.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This example demonstrates a type of resonance and the frequencies that produce standing waves can be referred to as *resonant frequencies*.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Next, consider the same string of length *L*, but this time it is only fixed at *x* = 0.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] At *x* = *L*, the string is free to move in the *y* direction.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] For example, the string might be tied at *x* = *L* to a ring that can slide freely up and down a pole.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The string again has small damping and is driven by a small driving force at *x* = 0.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] In this case, Equation (**1**) still describes the standing wave pattern that can form on the string, and the string has the same boundary condition of *y* = 0 at *x* = 0.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] However, at *x* = *L* where the string can move freely there should be an anti-node with maximal amplitude of *y*.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Equivalently, this boundary condition of the "free end" can be stated as *∂y/∂x* = 0 at *x* = *L*, which is in the form of the Sturm–Liouville formulation.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The intuition for this boundary condition *∂y/∂x* = 0 at *x* = *L* is that the motion of the "free end" will follow that of the point to its left.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This leads to a different set of wavelengths than in the two-fixed-ends example.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] In this example *n* only takes odd values.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Because *L* is an anti-node, it is an *odd* multiple of a quarter wavelength.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Thus the fundamental mode in this example only has one quarter of a complete sine cycle–zero at *x* = 0 and the first peak at *x* = *L*–the first harmonic has three quarters of a complete sine cycle, and so on.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This example also demonstrates a type of resonance and the frequencies that produce standing waves are called *resonant frequencies*.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Consider a standing wave in a pipe of length *L*.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The air inside the pipe serves as the medium for longitudinal sound waves traveling to the right or left through the pipe.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] While the transverse waves on the string from the previous examples vary in their displacement perpendicular to the direction of wave motion, the waves traveling through the air in the pipe vary in terms of their pressure and longitudinal displacement along the direction of wave motion.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The wave propagates by alternately compressing and expanding air in segments of the pipe, which displaces the air slightly from its rest position and transfers energy to neighboring segments through the forces exerted by the alternating high and low air pressures.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Equations resembling those for the wave on a string can be written for the change in pressure Δ*p* due to a right- or left-traveling wave in the pipe.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This formula for the pressure is of the same form as Equation (**1**), so a stationary pressure wave forms that is fixed in space and oscillates in time.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] If the end of a pipe is closed, the pressure is maximal since the closed end of the pipe exerts a force that restricts the movement of air.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This corresponds to a pressure anti-node (which is a node for molecular motions, because the molecules near the closed end cannot move).
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] If the end of the pipe is open, the pressure variations are very small, corresponding to a pressure node (which is an anti-node for molecular motions, because the molecules near the open end can move freely).
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The exact location of the pressure node at an open end is actually slightly beyond the open end of the pipe, so the effective length of the pipe for the purpose of determining resonant frequencies is slightly longer than its physical length.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This difference in length is ignored in this example.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] In terms of reflections, open ends partially reflect waves back into the pipe, allowing some energy to be released into the outside air.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Ideally, closed ends reflect the entire wave back in the other direction.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] First consider a pipe that is open at both ends, for example an open organ pipe or a recorder.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Next, consider a pipe that is open at *x* = 0 (and therefore has a pressure node) and closed at *x* = *L* (and therefore has a pressure anti-node).
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The closed "free end" boundary condition for the pressure at *x* = *L* can be stated as *∂(Δp)/∂x* = 0, which is in the form of the Sturm–Liouville formulation.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The intuition for this boundary condition *∂(Δp)/∂x* = 0 at *x* = *L* is that the pressure of the closed end will follow that of the point to its left.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Examples of this setup include a bottle and a clarinet.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This pipe has boundary conditions analogous to the string with only one fixed end.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] For the case where one end is closed, *n* only takes odd values just like in the case of the string fixed at only one end.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] So far, the wave has been written in terms of its pressure as a function of position *x* and time.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Alternatively, the wave can be written in terms of its longitudinal displacement of air, where air in a segment of the pipe moves back and forth slightly in the *x*-direction as the pressure varies and waves travel in either or both directions.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] In terms of longitudinal displacement, closed ends of pipes correspond to nodes since air movement is restricted and open ends correspond to anti-nodes since the air is free to move.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] A similar, easier to visualize phenomenon occurs in longitudinal waves propagating along a spring.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] We can also consider a pipe that is closed at both ends.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] In this case, both ends will be pressure anti-nodes or equivalently both ends will be displacement nodes.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This example is analogous to the case where both ends are open, except the standing wave pattern has a π⁄2 phase shift along the *x*-direction to shift the location of the nodes and anti-nodes.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] For example, the longest wavelength that resonates–the fundamental mode–is again twice the length of the pipe, except that the ends of the pipe have pressure anti-nodes instead of pressure nodes.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Between the ends there is one pressure node.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] A Rubens tube provides a way to visualize the pressure variations of the standing waves in a tube with two closed ends.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Next, consider transverse waves that can move along a two dimensional surface within a rectangular boundary of length *Lx* in the *x*-direction and length *Ly* in the *y*-direction.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Examples of this type of wave are water waves in a pool or waves on a rectangular sheet that has been pulled taut.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The waves displace the surface in the *z*-direction, with *z* = 0 defined as the height of the surface when it is still.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This is an eigenvalue problem where the frequencies correspond to eigenvalues that then correspond to frequency-specific modes or eigenfunctions.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Specifically, this is a form of the Helmholtz equation and it can be solved using separation of variables.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This leads to two coupled ordinary differential equations.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This *x*-dependence is sinusoidal–recalling Euler's formula–with constants *A**k**x* and *B**k**x* determined by the boundary conditions.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The constants that determine the exact sinusoidal functions depend on the boundary conditions and initial conditions.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] To see how the boundary conditions apply, consider an example like the sheet that has been pulled taut where *z*(*x*,*y*,*t*) must be zero all around the rectangular boundary.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] For the *x* dependence, *z*(*x*,*y*,*t*) must vary in a way that it can be zero at both *x* = 0 and *x* = *L**x* for all values of *y* and *t*.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] So, standing waves inside this fixed rectangular boundary oscillate in time at certain resonant frequencies parameterized by the integers *n* and *m*.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] As they oscillate in time, they do not travel and their spatial variation is sinusoidal in both the *x*- and *y*-directions such that they satisfy the boundary conditions.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The fundamental mode, *n* = 1 and *m* = 1, has a single antinode in the middle of the rectangle.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Varying *n* and *m* gives complicated but predictable two-dimensional patterns of nodes and antinodes inside the rectangle.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] From the dispersion relation, in certain situations different modes–meaning different combinations of *n* and *m*–may resonate at the same frequency even though they have different shapes for their *x*- and *y*-dependence.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Recalling that *ω* determines the eigenvalue in the Helmholtz equation above, the number of modes corresponding to each frequency relates to the frequency's multiplicity as an eigenvalue.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] If the two oppositely moving traveling waves are not of the same amplitude, they will not cancel completely at the nodes, the points where the waves are 180° out of phase, so the amplitude of the standing wave will not be zero at the nodes, but merely a minimum.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Standing wave ratio (SWR) is the ratio of the amplitude at the antinode (maximum) to the amplitude at the node (minimum).
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] A pure standing wave will have an infinite SWR.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] It will also have a constant phase at any point in space (but it may undergo a 180° inversion every half cycle).
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] A finite, non-zero SWR indicates a wave that is partially stationary and partially travelling.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Such waves can be decomposed into a superposition of two waves: a travelling wave component and a stationary wave component.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] An SWR of one indicates that the wave does not have a stationary component – it is purely a travelling wave, since the ratio of amplitudes is equal to 1.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] A pure standing wave does not transfer energy from the source to the destination.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] However, the wave is still subject to losses in the medium.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Such losses will manifest as a finite SWR, indicating a travelling wave component leaving the source to supply the losses.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Even though the SWR is now finite, it may still be the case that no energy reaches the destination because the travelling component is purely supplying the losses.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] However, in a lossless medium, a finite SWR implies a definite transfer of energy to the destination.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] One easy example to understand standing waves is two people shaking either end of a jump rope.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] If they shake in sync the rope can form a regular pattern of waves oscillating up and down, with stationary points along the rope where the rope is almost still (nodes) and points where the arc of the rope is maximum (antinodes).
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Standing waves are also observed in physical media such as strings and columns of air.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Any waves traveling along the medium will reflect back when they reach the end.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This effect is most noticeable in musical instruments where, at various multiples of a vibrating string or air column's natural frequency, a standing wave is created, allowing harmonics to be identified.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Nodes occur at fixed ends and anti-nodes at open ends.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] If fixed at only one end, only odd-numbered harmonics are available.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] At the open end of a pipe the anti-node will not be exactly at the end as it is altered by its contact with the air and so end correction is used to place it exactly.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The density of a string will affect the frequency at which harmonics will be produced; the greater the density the lower the frequency needs to be to produce a standing wave of the same harmonic.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Standing waves are also observed in optical media such as optical waveguides and optical cavities.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Lasers use optical cavities in the form of a pair of facing mirrors, which constitute a Fabry–Pérot interferometer.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The gain medium in the cavity (such as a crystal) emits light coherently, exciting standing waves of light in the cavity.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The wavelength of light is very short (in the range of nanometers, 10−9 m) so the standing waves are microscopic in size.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] One use for standing light waves is to measure small distances, using optical flats.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Interference between X-ray beams can form an X-ray standing wave (XSW) field.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Because of the short wavelength of X-rays (less than 1 nanometer), this phenomenon can be exploited for measuring atomic-scale events at material surfaces.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The XSW is generated in the region where an X-ray beam interferes with a diffracted beam from a nearly perfect single crystal surface or a reflection from an X-ray mirror.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] By tuning the crystal geometry or X-ray wavelength, the XSW can be translated in space, causing a shift in the X-ray fluorescence or photoelectron yield from the atoms near the surface.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] This shift can be analyzed to pinpoint the location of a particular atomic species relative to the underlying crystal structure or mirror surface.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The XSW method has been used to clarify the atomic-scale details of dopants in semiconductors, atomic and molecular adsorption on surfaces, and chemical transformations involved in catalysis.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Standing waves can be mechanically induced into a solid medium using resonance.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] One easy to understand example is two people shaking either end of a jump rope.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] If they shake in sync, the rope will form a regular pattern with nodes and antinodes and appear to be stationary, hence the name standing wave.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Similarly a cantilever beam can have a standing wave imposed on it by applying a base excitation.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] In this case the free end moves the greatest distance laterally compared to any location along the beam.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Such a device can be used as a sensor to track changes in frequency or phase of the resonance of the fiber.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] One application is as a measurement device for dimensional metrology.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] Standing surface waves on the Earth are observed as free oscillations of the Earth.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] The Faraday wave is a non-linear standing wave at the air-liquid interface induced by hydrodynamic instability.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] It can be used as a liquid-based template to assemble microscale materials.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] A seiche is an example of a standing wave in an enclosed body of water.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] It is characterised by the oscillatory behaviour of the water level at either end of the body and typically has a nodal point near the middle of the body where very little change in water level is observed.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] It should be distinguished from a simple storm surge where no oscillation is present.
[src:acoustics-physics/standing-wave] In sizeable lakes, the period of such oscillations may be between minutes and hours, for example Lake Geneva's longitudinal period is 73 minutes and its transversal seiche has a period of around 10 minutes, while Lake Huron can be seen to have resonances with periods between 1 and 2 hours.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] In music, **timbre** (/ˈtæmbər, ˈtɪm-, ˈtæ̃-/), also known as **tone color** or **tone quality** (from psychoacoustics), is the perceived sound of a musical note, sound or tone.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Timbre distinguishes sounds according to their source, such as choir voices and musical instruments.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] It also enables listeners to distinguish instruments in the same category (e.g., an oboe and a clarinet, both woodwind instruments).
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] In simple terms, timbre is what makes a particular musical instrument or human voice have a different sound from another, even when they play or sing the same note.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] For instance, it is the difference in sound between a guitar and a piano playing the same note at the same volume.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Both instruments can sound equally tuned in relation to each other as they play the same note, and while playing at the same amplitude level each instrument will still sound distinctive with its own unique tone color.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Musicians distinguish instruments based on their varied timbres, even instruments playing notes at the same pitch and volume.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] The physical characteristics that govern timbre include frequency spectrum and envelope.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Musicians can change timbre by modifying their singing or playing techniques.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] For example, a violinist can use different bowing styles or bow on different parts of the string.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] E.g., playing *sul tasto* produces a light, airy timbre, whereas *sul ponticello* produces a harsh, even, aggressive timbre.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] On electric guitar and electric piano, performers can change timbre using effects units and graphic equalizers.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Many commentators have decomposed timbre into component attributes.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] An example of a tonal sound is a musical sound that has a definite pitch, such as pressing a key on a piano; one sound with a noiselike character is white noise.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] The richness of a sound or note a musical instrument produces is sometimes described in terms of the sum of a number of distinct frequencies.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] The lowest frequency is called the *fundamental frequency*, and the pitch it produces is used to name the note, but the fundamental frequency is not always the dominant frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] The dominant frequency is the frequency that is most heard, and it is always a multiple of the fundamental frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] For example, the dominant frequency for the transverse flute is double the fundamental frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Other significant frequencies are called overtones of the fundamental frequency, which may include harmonics and partials.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Harmonics are whole-number multiples of the fundamental frequency, such as ×2, ×3, ×4, etc.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] There are also sometimes subharmonics at whole number *divisions* of the fundamental frequency.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Most instruments produce harmonic sounds, but many instruments produce partials and inharmonic tones, such as cymbals and other indefinite-pitched instruments.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] When the tuning note in an orchestra or concert band is played, the sound is a combination of 440 Hz, 880 Hz, 1320 Hz, 1760 Hz, and so on.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Each instrument in the orchestra or concert band produces a different combination of these frequencies, as well as harmonics and overtones.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] The sound waves of the different frequencies overlap and combine, and the balance of these amplitudes is a major factor in the characteristic sound of each instrument.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Similarly, the inharmonic spectra of Balinese metallophones combined with harmonic instruments such as the stringed rebab or the voice, are related to the five-note near-equal tempered slendro scale commonly found in Indonesian gamelan music.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] The timbre of a sound is also greatly affected by the following aspects of its *envelope*: attack time and characteristics, decay, sustain, release (ADSR envelope), and transients.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Thus, these are all common controls on professional synthesizers.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] The envelope is the overall amplitude structure of a sound.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Instrumental timbre played an increasing role in the practice of orchestration during the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Berlioz and Wagner made significant contributions to its development during the nineteenth century.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] For example, Wagner's "Sleep motif" from Act 3 of his opera *Die Walküre*, features a descending chromatic scale that passes through a gamut of orchestral timbres.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] First the woodwind (flute, followed by oboe), then the massed sound of strings with the violins carrying the melody, and finally the brass (French horns).
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Mahler's approach to orchestration illustrates the increasing role of differentiated timbres in music of the early twentieth century.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] "a seven-bar link to the trio consisting of an extension in diminuendo of the repeated As ... though now rising in a succession of piled octaves which moreover leap-frog with Cs added to the As.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] In rock music from the late 1960s to the 2000s, the timbre of specific sounds is important to a song.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] For example, in heavy metal music, the sonic impact of the heavily amplified, heavily distorted power chord played on electric guitar through very loud guitar amplifiers and rows of speaker cabinets is an essential part of the style's musical identity.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Often, listeners can identify an instrument, even at different pitches and loudness, in different environments, and with different players.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] In the case of the clarinet, acoustic analysis shows waveforms irregular enough to suggest three instruments rather than one.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] "[C]ertain strong regularities in the acoustic waveform of the above instruments must exist which are invariant with respect to the above variables".
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] However, Robert Erickson argues that there are few regularities and they do not explain our "...powers of recognition and identification." He suggests borrowing the concept of subjective constancy from studies of vision and visual perception.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Psychoacoustic experiments from the 1960s onwards tried to elucidate the nature of timbre.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] One method involves playing pairs of sounds to listeners, then using a multidimensional scaling algorithm to aggregate their dissimilarity judgments into a timbre space.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] The most consistent outcomes from such experiments are that brightness or spectral energy distribution, and the *bite*, or rate and synchronicity and rise time, of the attack are important factors.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] The concept of tristimulus originates in the world of color, describing the way three primary colors can be mixed together to create a given color.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] By analogy, the musical tristimulus measures the mixture of harmonics in a given sound, grouped into three sections.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] It is basically a proposal of reducing a huge number of sound partials, which can amount to dozens or hundreds in some cases, down to only three values.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] However, more evidence, studies and applications would be needed regarding this type of representation, in order to validate it.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] The term "brightness" is also used in discussions of sound timbres, in a rough analogy with visual brightness.
[src:acoustics-physics/timbre] Timbre researchers consider brightness to be one of the perceptually strongest distinctions between sounds and formalize it acoustically as an indication of the amount of high-frequency content in a sound, using a measure such as the spectral centroid.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound is used in many different fields.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic devices are used to detect objects and measure distances.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound imaging or sonography is often used in medicine.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] In the nondestructive testing of products and structures, ultrasound is used to detect invisible flaws.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Industrially, ultrasound is used for cleaning, mixing, and accelerating chemical processes.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Animals such as bats and porpoises use ultrasound for locating prey and obstacles.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Acoustics, the science of sound, starts as far back as Pythagoras in the 6th century BC, who wrote on the mathematical properties of stringed instruments.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Echolocation in bats was discovered by Lazzaro Spallanzani in 1794, when he demonstrated that bats hunted and navigated by inaudible sound, not vision.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Francis Galton in 1893 invented the Galton whistle, an adjustable whistle that produced ultrasound, which he used to measure the hearing range of humans and other animals, demonstrating that many animals could hear sounds above the hearing range of humans.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The first article on the history of ultrasound was written in 1948.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] According to its author, during the First World War, a Russian engineer named Chilowski submitted an idea for submarine detection to the French Government.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The latter invited Paul Langevin, then Director of the School of Physics and Chemistry in Paris, to evaluate it.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Chilowski's proposal was to excite a cylindrical, mica condenser by a high-frequency Poulsen arc at approximately 100 kHz and thus to generate an ultrasound beam for detecting submerged objects.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The idea of locating underwater obstacles had been suggested prior by L.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Richardson, following the *Titanic* disaster.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Richardson had proposed to position a high-frequency hydraulic whistle at the focus of a mirror and use the beam for locating submerged navigational hazards.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] A prototype was built by Sir Charles Parsons, the inventor of the vapour turbine, but the device was found not to be suitable for this purpose.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Langevin's device made use of the piezoelectric effect, which he had been acquainted with whilst a student at the laboratory of Jacques and Pierre Curie.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Langevin calculated and built an ultrasound transducer comprising a thin sheet of quartz sandwiched between two steel plates.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Langevin was the first to report cavitation-related bioeffects from ultrasound.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound is defined by the American National Standards Institute as "sound at frequencies greater than 20 kHz".
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] In air at atmospheric pressure, ultrasonic waves have wavelengths of 1.9 cm or less.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound can be generated at very high frequencies; ultrasound is used for sonochemistry at frequencies up to multiple hundreds of kilohertz.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Medical imaging equipment uses frequencies in the MHz range.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] UHF ultrasound waves have been generated as high as the gigahertz range.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Characterizing extremely high-frequency ultrasound poses challenges, as such rapid movement causes waveforms to steepen and form shock waves.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The upper frequency limit in humans (approximately 20 kHz) is due to limitations of the middle ear.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Auditory sensation can occur if high‐intensity ultrasound is fed directly into the human skull and reaches the cochlea through bone conduction, without passing through the middle ear.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Children can hear some high-pitched sounds that older adults cannot hear, because in humans the upper limit pitch of hearing tends to decrease with age.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] An American cell phone company has used this to create ring signals that supposedly are only audible to younger humans, but many older people can hear the signals, which may be because of the considerable variation of age-related deterioration in the upper hearing threshold.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Bats use a variety of ultrasonic ranging (echolocation) techniques to detect their prey.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] They can detect frequencies beyond 100 kHz, possibly up to 200 kHz.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Many insects have good ultrasonic hearing, and most of these are nocturnal insects listening for echolocating bats.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] These include many groups of moths, beetles, praying mantises and lacewings.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Upon hearing a bat, some insects will make evasive manoeuvres to escape being caught.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic frequencies trigger a reflex action in the noctuid moth that causes it to drop slightly in its flight to evade attack.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Tiger moths also emit clicks which may disturb bats' echolocation, and in other cases may advertise the fact that they are poisonous by emitting sound.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Dogs and cats' hearing range extends into the ultrasound; the top end of a dog's hearing range is about 45 kHz, while a cat's is 64 kHz.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The wild ancestors of cats and dogs evolved this higher hearing range to hear high-frequency sounds made by their preferred prey, small rodents.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] A dog whistle is a whistle that emits ultrasound, used for training and calling dogs.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The frequency of most dog whistles is within the range of 23 to 54 kHz.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Toothed whales, including dolphins, can hear ultrasound and use such sounds in their navigational system (biosonar) to orient and to capture prey.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Porpoises have the highest known upper hearing limit at around 160 kHz.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Several types of fish can detect ultrasound.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] In the order Clupeiformes, members of the subfamily Alosinae (shad) have been shown to be able to detect sounds up to 180 kHz, while the other subfamilies (e.g. herrings) can hear only up to 4 kHz.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] No bird species have been reported to be sensitive to ultrasound.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Commercial ultrasonic systems have been sold for supposed indoors electronic pest control and outdoors ultrasonic algae control.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] However, no scientific evidence exists on the success of such devices for these purposes.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] An ultrasonic level or sensing system requires no contact with the target.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] For many processes in the medical, pharmaceutical, military and general industries this is an advantage over inline sensors that may contaminate the liquids inside a vessel or tube or that may be clogged by the product.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Both continuous wave and pulsed systems are used.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The principle behind a pulsed-ultrasonic technology is that the transmit signal consists of short bursts of ultrasonic energy.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] After each burst, the electronics looks for a return signal within a small window of time corresponding to the time it takes for the energy to pass through the vessel.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Only a signal received during this window will qualify for additional signal processing.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] A popular consumer application of ultrasonic ranging was the Polaroid SX-70 camera, which included a lightweight transducer system to focus the camera automatically.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Polaroid later licensed this ultrasound technology and it became the basis of a variety of ultrasonic products.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] A common ultrasound application is an automatic door opener, where an ultrasonic sensor detects a person's approach and opens the door.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic sensors are also used to detect intruders; the ultrasound can cover a wide area from a single point.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The flow in pipes or open channels can be measured by ultrasonic flowmeters, which measure the average velocity of flowing liquid.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] In rheology, an acoustic rheometer relies on analyzing the propagation of ultrasound to determine a fluid's viscosity.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] In fluid mechanics, fluid flow can be measured using an ultrasonic flow meter based on the Doppler effect.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic testing is a type of nondestructive testing commonly used to find flaws in materials and to measure the thickness of objects.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Frequencies of 2 to 10 MHz are common, but for special purposes other frequencies are used.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Inspection may be manual or automated and is an essential part of modern manufacturing processes.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Most metals can be inspected as well as plastics and aerospace composites.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Lower frequency ultrasound (50–500 kHz) can also be used to inspect less dense materials such as wood, concrete and cement.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound inspection of welded joints has been an alternative to radiography for nondestructive testing since the 1960s.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic inspection eliminates the use of ionizing radiation, with safety and cost benefits.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound can also provide additional information such as the depth of flaws in a welded joint.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic inspection has progressed from manual methods to computerized systems that automate much of the process.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] An ultrasonic test of a joint can identify the existence of flaws, measure their size, and identify their location.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Not all welded materials are equally amenable to ultrasonic inspection; some materials have a large grain size that produces a high level of background noise in measurements.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic thickness measurement is one technique used to monitor quality of welds.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] A common use of ultrasound is in underwater range finding; this use is also called sonar.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] An ultrasonic pulse is generated in a particular direction.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] If there is an object in the path of this pulse, part or all of the pulse will be reflected back to the transmitter as an echo and can be detected through the receiver path.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] By measuring the difference in time between the pulse being transmitted and the echo being received, it is possible to determine the distance.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The measured travel time of Sonar pulses in water is strongly dependent on the temperature and the salinity of the water.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic ranging is also applied for measurement in air and for short distances.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] For example, hand-held ultrasonic measuring tools can rapidly measure the layout of rooms.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Although range finding underwater is performed at both sub-audible and audible frequencies for great distances (1 to several kilometers), ultrasonic range finding is used when distances are shorter and the accuracy of the distance measurement is desired to be better.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic measurements may be limited through barrier layers with large salinity, temperature or vortex differences.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ranging in water varies from about hundreds to thousands of meters, but can be performed with centimeters to meters for accuracy.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The potential for ultrasonic imaging of objects, in which a 3 GHz sound wave could produce resolution comparable to an optical image, was recognized by Sergei Sokolov in 1939.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Such frequencies were not possible at the time, and what technology did exist produced relatively low-contrast images with poor sensitivity.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic imaging uses frequencies of 2 megahertz and higher; the shorter wavelength allows resolution of small internal details in structures and tissues.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The power density is generally less than 1 watt per square centimetre to avoid heating and cavitation effects in the object under examination.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic imaging applications include industrial nondestructive testing, quality control and medical uses.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Imaging can be viewed as ranging with added angular information.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Acoustic microscopy is the technique of using sound waves to visualize structures too small to be resolved by the human eye.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] High and ultra high frequencies up to several gigahertz are used in acoustic microscopes.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The reflection and diffraction of sound waves from microscopic structures can yield information not available with light.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Medical ultrasound is an ultrasound-based diagnostic medical imaging technique used to visualize muscles, tendons, and many internal organs to capture their size, structure and any pathological lesions with real time tomographic images.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound has been used by radiologists and sonographers to image the human body for at least 50 years and has become a widely used diagnostic tool.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The technology is relatively inexpensive and portable, especially when compared with other techniques, such as magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) and computed tomography (CT).
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound is also used to visualize fetuses during routine and emergency prenatal care.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Such diagnostic applications used during pregnancy are referred to as obstetric sonography.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound is also increasingly being used in trauma and first aid cases, with emergency ultrasound being used by some EMT response teams.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Furthermore, ultrasound is used in remote diagnosis cases where teleconsultation is required, such as scientific experiments in space or mobile sports team diagnosis, as the equipment is more portable compared to other imaging methods.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] According to RadiologyInfo, ultrasounds are useful in the detection of pelvic abnormalities and can involve techniques known as abdominal (transabdominal) ultrasound, vaginal (transvaginal or endovaginal) ultrasound in women, and also rectal (transrectal) ultrasound in men.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] In Doppler ultrasonography, the speed of objects is measured along with their positions.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] This is especially useful for analyzing blood flow in the heart (Doppler echocardiography).
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] As currently applied in the medical field, properly performed ultrasound poses no known risks to the patient.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Sonography does not use ionizing radiation, and the power levels used for imaging are too low to cause adverse heating or pressure effects in tissue.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Although the long-term effects due to ultrasound exposure at diagnostic intensity are still unknown, currently most doctors feel that the benefits to patients outweigh the risks.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Diagnostic ultrasound is used externally in horses for evaluation of soft tissue and tendon injuries, and internally in particular for reproductive work – evaluation of the reproductive tract of the mare and pregnancy detection.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] It may also be used in an external manner in stallions for evaluation of testicular condition and diameter as well as internally for reproductive evaluation (deferent duct etc.).
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] By 2005, ultrasound technology began to be used by the beef cattle industry to improve animal health and the yield of cattle operations.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound is used to evaluate fat thickness, rib eye area, and intramuscular fat in living animals.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] It is also used to evaluate the health and characteristics of unborn calves.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound technology provides a means for cattle producers to obtain information that can be used to improve the breeding and husbandry of cattle.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The technology can be expensive, and it requires a substantial time commitment for continuous data collection and operator training.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Nevertheless, this technology has proven useful in managing and running a cattle breeding operation.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] High-power applications of ultrasound often use frequencies between 20 kHz and a few hundred kHz.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Intensities can be very high; above 10 watts per square centimeter, cavitation can be inducted in liquid media, and some applications use up to 1000 watts per square centimeter.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Such high intensities can induce chemical changes or produce significant effects by direct mechanical action, and can inactivate harmful microorganisms.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound has been used since the 1940s by physical and occupational therapists for treating connective tissue: ligaments, tendons, and fascia (and also scar tissue).
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Conditions for which ultrasound may be used for treatment include the follow examples: ligament sprains, muscle strains, tendonitis, joint inflammation, plantar fasciitis, metatarsalgia, facet irritation, impingement syndrome, bursitis, rheumatoid arthritis, osteoarthritis, and scar tissue adhesion.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Relatively high power ultrasound can break up stony deposits or tissue, increase skin permeability, accelerate the effect of drugs in a targeted area, assist in the measurement of the elastic properties of tissue, and can be used to sort cells or small particles for research.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic impact treatment (UIT) uses ultrasound to enhance the mechanical and physical properties of metals.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] It is a metallurgical processing technique in which ultrasonic energy is applied to a metal object.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic treatment can result in controlled residual compressive stress, grain refinement and grain size reduction.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Low and high cycle fatigue are enhanced and have been documented to provide increases up to ten times greater than non-UIT specimens.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Additionally, UIT has proven effective in addressing stress corrosion cracking, corrosion fatigue and related issues.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] When the UIT tool, made up of the ultrasonic transducer, pins and other components, comes into contact with the work piece it acoustically couples with the work piece, creating harmonic resonance.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] This harmonic resonance is performed at a carefully calibrated frequency, to which metals respond very favorably.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Depending on the desired effects of treatment a combination of different frequencies and displacement amplitude is applied.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] These frequencies range between 25 and 55 kHz, with the displacement amplitude of the resonant body of between 22 and 50 μm (0.00087 and 0.0020 in).
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] UIT devices rely on magnetostrictive transducers.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonication offers great potential in the processing of liquids and slurries, by improving the mixing and chemical reactions in various applications and industries.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonication generates alternating low-pressure and high-pressure waves in liquids, leading to the formation and violent collapse of small vacuum bubbles.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] This phenomenon is termed cavitation and causes high speed impinging liquid jets and strong hydrodynamic shear-forces.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] These effects are used for the deagglomeration and milling of micrometre and nanometre-size materials as well as for the disintegration of cells or the mixing of reactants.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] In this aspect, ultrasonication is an alternative to high-speed mixers and agitator bead mills.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic foils under the moving wire in a paper machine will use the shock waves from the imploding bubbles to distribute the cellulose fibres more uniformly in the produced paper web, which will make a stronger paper with more even surfaces.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Furthermore, chemical reactions benefit from the free radicals created by the cavitation as well as from the energy input and the material transfer through boundary layers.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] For many processes, this sonochemical (see sonochemistry) effect leads to a substantial reduction in the reaction time, like in the transesterification of oil into biodiesel.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Substantial ultrasonic intensity and high ultrasonic vibration amplitudes are required for many processing applications, such as nano-crystallization, nano-emulsification, deagglomeration, extraction, cell disruption, as well as many others.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Commonly, a process is first tested on a laboratory scale to prove feasibility and establish some of the required ultrasonic exposure parameters.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] After this phase is complete, the process is transferred to a pilot (bench) scale for flow-through pre-production optimization and then to an industrial scale for continuous production.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] During these scale-up steps, it is essential to make sure that all local exposure conditions (ultrasonic amplitude, cavitation intensity, time spent in the active cavitation zone, etc.) stay the same.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] If this condition is met, the quality of the final product remains at the optimized level, while the productivity is increased by a predictable "scale-up factor".
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The productivity increase results from the fact that laboratory, bench and industrial-scale ultrasonic processor systems incorporate progressively larger ultrasonic horns, able to generate progressively larger high-intensity cavitation zones and, therefore, to process more material per unit of time.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] It is important to point out that increasing the power of the ultrasonic processor alone does *not* result in direct scalability, since it may be (and frequently is) accompanied by a reduction in the ultrasonic amplitude and cavitation intensity.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] During direct scale-up, all processing conditions must be maintained, while the power rating of the equipment is increased in order to enable the operation of a larger ultrasonic horn.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] A researcher at the Industrial Materials Research Institute, Alessandro Malutta, devised an experiment that demonstrated the trapping action of ultrasonic standing waves on wood pulp fibers diluted in water and their parallel orienting into the equidistant pressure planes.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The time to orient the fibers in equidistant planes is measured with a laser and an electro-optical sensor.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] This could provide the paper industry a quick on-line fiber size measurement system.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] A somewhat different implementation was demonstrated at Pennsylvania State University using a microchip which generated a pair of perpendicular standing surface acoustic waves allowing to position particles equidistant to each other on a grid.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] This experiment, called acoustic tweezers, can be used for applications in material sciences, biology, physics, chemistry and nanotechnology.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic cleaners, sometimes mistakenly called *supersonic cleaners*, are used at frequencies from 20 to 40 kHz for jewellery, lenses and other optical parts, watches, dental instruments, surgical instruments, diving regulators and industrial parts.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] An ultrasonic cleaner works mostly by energy released from the collapse of millions of microscopic cavitation bubbles near the dirty surface.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The collapsing bubbles form tiny shockwaves that break up and disperse contaminants on the object's surface.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Similar to ultrasonic cleaning, biological cells including bacteria can be disintegrated.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] High power ultrasound produces cavitation that facilitates particle disintegration or reactions.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] This has uses in biological science for analytical or chemical purposes (sonication and sonoporation) and in killing bacteria in sewage.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] High power ultrasound can disintegrate corn slurry and enhance liquefaction and saccharification for higher ethanol yield in dry corn milling plants.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The ultrasonic humidifier, one type of nebulizer (a device that creates a very fine spray), is a popular type of humidifier.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] It works by vibrating a metal plate at ultrasonic frequencies to nebulize (sometimes incorrectly called "atomize") the water.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Because the water is not heated for evaporation, it produces a cool mist.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The ultrasonic pressure waves nebulize not only the water but also materials in the water including calcium, other minerals, viruses, fungi, bacteria, and other impurities.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Illness caused by impurities that reside in a humidifier's reservoir fall under the heading of "Humidifier Fever".
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic humidifiers are frequently used in aeroponics, where they are generally referred to as foggers.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] In ultrasonic welding of plastics, high frequency (15 kHz to 40 kHz) low amplitude vibration is used to create heat by way of friction between the materials to be joined.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The interface of the two parts is specially designed to concentrate the energy for maximum weld strength.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Power ultrasound in the 20–100 kHz range is used in chemistry.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The ultrasound does not interact directly with molecules to induce the chemical change, as its typical wavelength (in the millimeter range) is too long compared to the molecules.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Instead, the energy causes cavitation which generates extremes of temperature and pressure in the liquid where the reaction happens.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound also breaks up solids and removes passivating layers of inert material to give a larger surface area for the reaction to occur over.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Both of these effects make the reaction faster.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] In 2008, Atul Kumar reported synthesis of Hantzsch esters and polyhydroquinoline derivatives via multi-component reaction protocol in aqueous micelles using ultrasound.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound is used in extraction, using different frequencies.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] When applied in specific configurations, ultrasound can produce short bursts of light in a phenomenon known as sonoluminescence.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound is used when characterizing particulates through the technique of ultrasound attenuation spectroscopy or by observing electroacoustic phenomena or by transcranial pulsed ultrasound.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Audio can be propagated by modulated ultrasound.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] A formerly popular consumer application of ultrasound was in television remote controls for adjusting volume and changing channels.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Introduced by Zenith in the late 1950s, the system used a hand-held remote control containing short rod resonators struck by small hammers, and a microphone on the set.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Filters and detectors discriminated between the various operations.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The principal advantages were that no battery was needed in the hand-held control box and, unlike radio waves, the ultrasound was unlikely to affect neighboring sets.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasound remained in use until displaced by infrared systems starting in the late 1980s.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] In July 2015, *The Economist* reported that researchers at the University of California, Berkeley have conducted ultrasound studies using graphene diaphragms.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The thinness and low weight of graphene combined with its strength make it an effective material to use in ultrasound communications.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] One suggested application of the technology would be underwater communications, where radio waves typically do not travel well.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Ultrasonic signals have been used in "audio beacons" for cross-device tracking of Internet users.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Occupational exposure to ultrasound in excess of 120 dB may lead to hearing loss.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] Exposure in excess of 155 dB may produce heating effects that are harmful to the human body, and it has been calculated that exposures above 180 dB may lead to death.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The UK's independent Advisory Group on Non-ionising Radiation (AGNIR) produced a report in 2010, which was published by the UK Health Protection Agency (HPA).
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] This report recommended an exposure limit for the general public to airborne ultrasound sound pressure levels (SPL) of 70 dB (at 20 kHz), and 100 dB (at 25 kHz and above).
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] In medical ultrasound, guidelines exist to prevent inertial cavitation from happening.
[src:acoustics-physics/ultrasound] The risk of inertial cavitation damage is expressed by the mechanical index.
